47
00:03:16,193 --> 00:03:16,253
[SPEAKER_17]: OK.

48
00:03:24,445 --> 00:03:31,620
[SPEAKER_13]: The Housing Authority right now has a portfolio of 851 affordable housing units that are located in Medford.

49
00:03:32,127 --> 00:03:43,993
[SPEAKER_13]: I'll touch upon just a moment from now on the addition of 22 units through the redevelopment of 121 Riverside salt install project construction project.

50
00:03:44,873 --> 00:03:46,354
[SPEAKER_13]: But at this point in time, it's 851.

51
00:03:47,594 --> 00:03:49,315
[SPEAKER_13]: Those units are all deeply affordable.

52
00:03:50,036 --> 00:03:56,419
[SPEAKER_13]: And in so far as 121 Riverside is concerned, the next slide.

53
00:04:01,667 --> 00:04:06,530
[SPEAKER_13]: The Saltonstone renovation, that project closed in May of this year.

54
00:04:07,410 --> 00:04:17,596
[SPEAKER_13]: That construction project is $105 million that we are investing in the redevelopment of that site.

55
00:04:18,216 --> 00:04:21,658
[SPEAKER_13]: That site was built in the mid to late 60s.

56
00:04:22,319 --> 00:04:26,681
[SPEAKER_13]: It needs a great deal of renovation of that.

57
00:04:27,122 --> 00:04:29,423
[SPEAKER_13]: And that is a total gut

58
00:04:30,718 --> 00:04:31,779
[SPEAKER_13]: construction project.

59
00:04:32,599 --> 00:04:41,984
[SPEAKER_13]: Modernization of the 200 existing units, they include new central AC, ventilation, plumbing, electrical kitchens, and baths, and community space.

60
00:04:42,004 --> 00:04:47,267
[SPEAKER_13]: And as I indicated, an additional 22 affordable units will be created.

61
00:04:47,807 --> 00:04:51,529
[SPEAKER_13]: If you look at the picture on this page, you'll see the 11th floor.

62
00:04:52,890 --> 00:04:55,371
[SPEAKER_13]: You'll see the 11th floor in the picture at the top.

63
00:04:56,492 --> 00:04:58,773
[SPEAKER_13]: That is when you walk out of the elevator.

64
00:04:59,278 --> 00:05:04,362
[SPEAKER_13]: The first thing you see is if the wall is still there is the opposite wall.

65
00:05:05,342 --> 00:05:08,965
[SPEAKER_13]: We actually are taking down the facade of the building.

66
00:05:09,806 --> 00:05:15,510
[SPEAKER_13]: The brick facade is coming off and behind that is the cinder block that holds that up.

67
00:05:15,930 --> 00:05:17,951
[SPEAKER_13]: That is being taken down if you were to drive by.

68
00:05:19,208 --> 00:05:20,229
[SPEAKER_13]: that's self-installed now.

69
00:05:20,469 --> 00:05:27,373
[SPEAKER_13]: If you were on the highway going into Boston, if you looked up, you'll see on the 11th floor plastic, because there are no walls.

70
00:05:28,113 --> 00:05:38,299
[SPEAKER_13]: So that when you come out of the elevator, now you don't even see the far wall that's pictured here, because there is no far wall, because we're putting in additional support into the building itself.

71
00:05:39,179 --> 00:05:43,161
[SPEAKER_13]: That is necessary for a building of that age.

72
00:05:44,405 --> 00:05:53,698
[SPEAKER_13]: That's our first construction project, our first redevelopment or reinvestment into the Housing Authority's property.

73
00:05:54,459 --> 00:05:56,081
[SPEAKER_13]: Walklane Court is the second.

74
00:05:56,942 --> 00:05:58,164
[SPEAKER_13]: Gabriel Ciccarello.

75
00:05:58,570 --> 00:06:00,811
[SPEAKER_13]: is our Director of Modernization and Procurement.

76
00:06:00,851 --> 00:06:06,555
[SPEAKER_13]: Gabe, in a moment, is going to go through what we're specifically doing at Walkling.

77
00:06:07,155 --> 00:06:17,181
[SPEAKER_13]: But Walkling is expected to close in phase one of that project in June of next year.

78
00:06:20,623 --> 00:06:27,827
[SPEAKER_13]: Thirdly is that we are looking for further redevelopment of the Housing Authority's properties

79
00:06:28,583 --> 00:06:37,042
[SPEAKER_13]: And we're looking specifically at the Pre Village, where we're currently undertaking a physical needs assessment of the property.

80
00:06:37,744 --> 00:06:38,245
[SPEAKER_13]: And we're also

81
00:06:39,168 --> 00:06:47,332
[SPEAKER_13]: investigating what efforts are necessary for our other sites to modernize the Housing Authority's properties.

82
00:06:48,213 --> 00:06:50,574
[SPEAKER_13]: All of the properties are fairly old.

83
00:06:51,514 --> 00:06:58,638
[SPEAKER_13]: Some of them do not meet current needs, and that's where we are with the Walkland Court project.

84
00:07:00,458 --> 00:07:01,718
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm going to let Gabe go further.

85
00:07:02,018 --> 00:07:07,039
[SPEAKER_13]: And what I'd ask is, if you have any questions, if there are any questions, we'll certainly be glad to answer those.

86
00:07:07,559 --> 00:07:11,560
[SPEAKER_13]: But if you'd like to hold those to the end, we'll be more than happy to do that collectively.

87
00:07:12,160 --> 00:07:12,540
[SPEAKER_17]: Absolutely.

88
00:07:12,720 --> 00:07:12,980
[SPEAKER_13]: All right.

89
00:07:13,020 --> 00:07:13,360
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

90
00:07:13,940 --> 00:07:19,701
[SPEAKER_13]: In addition, before I continue on, Margaret Moran is our development consultant.

91
00:07:19,801 --> 00:07:27,983
[SPEAKER_13]: And she is here with us tonight, who will be able to answer any technical questions that you may have about the ongoing project.

92
00:07:28,783 --> 00:07:29,083
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

93
00:07:31,049 --> 00:07:31,930
[SPEAKER_02]: Good evening, everybody.

94
00:07:32,270 --> 00:07:34,031
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you so much for meeting with us this evening.

95
00:07:34,812 --> 00:07:36,753
[SPEAKER_02]: My name's Gabe Ciccariello, as Jeff stated.

96
00:07:36,813 --> 00:07:40,996
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm the Director of Modernization and Procurement with the Medford Housing Authority.

97
00:07:41,396 --> 00:07:45,099
[SPEAKER_02]: I've been working with Jeff in public housing for over 20 years now.

98
00:07:45,699 --> 00:07:49,082
[SPEAKER_02]: I joined him in Medford a few months after he came here.

99
00:07:49,915 --> 00:07:56,619
[SPEAKER_02]: And as Jeff stated, we operate, manage, and own a little over 850 units of public housing.

100
00:07:56,679 --> 00:08:02,543
[SPEAKER_02]: We also administer close to 1,000 Section 8 vouchers or affordable housing vouchers.

101
00:08:02,583 --> 00:08:08,246
[SPEAKER_02]: So the Medford Housing Authority is the largest provider of affordable housing in the city.

102
00:08:10,267 --> 00:08:15,368
[SPEAKER_02]: We're going to get into Walkland Court a little bit, and kind of why we're here before you this evening.

103
00:08:15,988 --> 00:08:26,910
[SPEAKER_02]: So the existing site at Walkland Court, it's 144 units of state-aided public housing for existing low-income senior and disabled households.

104
00:08:28,470 --> 00:08:33,371
[SPEAKER_02]: All units there are deeply affordable, with the resident rent calculated at a maximum of 30% of their income.

105
00:08:38,255 --> 00:08:48,621
[SPEAKER_02]: Historically and to date, Walkman Court has received insufficient funding operating subsidy to address its physical needs.

106
00:08:48,682 --> 00:08:55,566
[SPEAKER_02]: There's just a few pictures we've included on this slide just to kind of show a little bit of what's going on within the building.

107
00:08:57,187 --> 00:09:02,870
[SPEAKER_02]: It's built in 1963 and suffers from a couple of the main things.

108
00:09:02,890 --> 00:09:05,352
[SPEAKER_02]: Number one, it's a poor physical condition, ventilation,

109
00:09:06,087 --> 00:09:08,828
[SPEAKER_02]: is poor, if non-existent within the buildings.

110
00:09:09,748 --> 00:09:13,110
[SPEAKER_02]: The plumbing, electrical are all original.

111
00:09:13,970 --> 00:09:18,532
[SPEAKER_02]: So it has not received what we like to call a comprehensive modernization since it was built.

112
00:09:19,512 --> 00:09:30,236
[SPEAKER_02]: But the biggest thing we really, how we look at the buildings is they lack the accessibility features really needed for an elderly and disabled population where half of the units need to be assessed by STAIRS.

113
00:09:31,237 --> 00:09:31,417
[SPEAKER_02]: So,

114
00:09:32,667 --> 00:09:46,533
[SPEAKER_02]: We like to inform everybody when we speak about this proposed redevelopment, we get a lot of what's called reasonable accommodations for our existing residents that live there that may have a second floor unit to get an accommodation to move from the second floor down to the first floor.

115
00:09:48,474 --> 00:09:52,035
[SPEAKER_02]: So the redevelopment of Walkland Court is a local priority.

116
00:09:53,176 --> 00:09:54,976
[SPEAKER_02]: And the replacement of the existing 144 units

117
00:09:56,720 --> 00:10:09,130
[SPEAKER_02]: And the construction of possible new units on the site is included in the fiscal year 21 through 25 city of Medford's housing production plan as a strategy to help assist the city's housing goals.

118
00:10:10,291 --> 00:10:18,097
[SPEAKER_02]: And really like what there's really like what better of a place to try to make an impact on affordable housing than an existing affordable housing site.

119
00:10:18,878 --> 00:10:22,321
[SPEAKER_02]: And so the new units at walk and code would help the city of Medford

120
00:10:22,728 --> 00:10:31,068
[SPEAKER_02]: meet 15% of its comprehensive plans goals to build 600 subsidized affordable units by fiscal year 2025.

121
00:10:35,817 --> 00:10:39,741
[SPEAKER_02]: So this is just a bird's eye view of the Walkman Court site.

122
00:10:40,542 --> 00:10:46,209
[SPEAKER_02]: So the existing site, it's nine two-story walk-up garden flat residential buildings.

123
00:10:46,409 --> 00:10:47,750
[SPEAKER_02]: Each building, they're identical.

124
00:10:47,770 --> 00:10:49,572
[SPEAKER_02]: They have 16 units per building.

125
00:10:50,213 --> 00:10:53,036
[SPEAKER_02]: And there's a community center kind of in the middle of the site.

126
00:10:53,737 --> 00:10:55,239
[SPEAKER_02]: And there's a small maintenance garage.

127
00:10:55,890 --> 00:11:00,135
[SPEAKER_02]: And it's a very interesting site, as you can see, because of how it's bordered.

128
00:11:00,796 --> 00:11:04,580
[SPEAKER_02]: To the west, you have commercial space with Whole Foods and Starbucks.

129
00:11:05,200 --> 00:11:10,066
[SPEAKER_02]: To your south, there's an industrial kind of commercial complex with mid-rise buildings.

130
00:11:11,638 --> 00:11:27,213
[SPEAKER_02]: And to your east and north, you have your traditional city of Medford, you know, the traditional neighborhood, single family, two family homes, and you have the Mystic River, an amazing amenity, which is like a 50-yard walk from the entrance to Whatcom Court.

131
00:11:28,554 --> 00:11:31,836
[SPEAKER_02]: And it's extremely accessible for seniors, disabled residents.

132
00:11:32,516 --> 00:11:34,317
[SPEAKER_02]: You get the bus lines on Boston Ave.

133
00:11:35,437 --> 00:11:44,121
[SPEAKER_02]: And now with the Tufts Green Line stop, it's an amazing location for affordable housing development for seniors and disabled residents.

134
00:11:47,503 --> 00:11:52,906
[SPEAKER_02]: So this is kind of an elevated view of what the proposed redevelopment would look like.

135
00:11:53,186 --> 00:11:56,507
[SPEAKER_02]: This is kind of from like the corner of North Street and Auburn Street.

136
00:11:58,052 --> 00:12:15,464
[SPEAKER_02]: What we've tried to do with this is kind of scale the buildings from smaller on the north part of the site, as you get to the southern portion of the site or by the train tracks or the industrial spaces across the train tracks, we scale up in the building.

137
00:12:15,544 --> 00:12:25,872
[SPEAKER_02]: So the direct abutters on North Street and Auburn Street, they'd be abutting similar structures to what's there right now, but we'd like to think a lot

138
00:12:26,610 --> 00:12:31,133
[SPEAKER_02]: nicer looking than the two-story brick flat buildings that are there.

139
00:12:32,254 --> 00:12:36,597
[SPEAKER_02]: So if they were to look out their rear window, they'd see a two-story townhouse building.

140
00:12:37,978 --> 00:12:40,599
[SPEAKER_02]: And those are the director photos on North Street and Auburn Street.

141
00:12:40,679 --> 00:12:52,067
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think what's possible with this redevelopment is 238 deeply affordable, high quality units in the walkable and transit hillside neighborhood.

142
00:12:53,445 --> 00:13:09,770
[SPEAKER_02]: Phase one, which would be that mid-rise building on the southern portion of the site, would be 198 deeply affordable units for seniors and people with disabilities, with construction slated to start in June of 2024.

143
00:13:09,810 --> 00:13:13,611
[SPEAKER_02]: Of those 198 units, 188 would be one bedroom units, and 10 of those being fully handicap accessible.

144
00:13:21,057 --> 00:13:24,058
[SPEAKER_02]: 10 of the 190 would be two bedrooms.

145
00:13:24,078 --> 00:13:27,159
[SPEAKER_15]: Can you just explain what you mean by fully accessible versus?

146
00:13:27,319 --> 00:13:41,442
[SPEAKER_02]: So what a fully handicap accessible unit would provide is you have wider doorways, a resident that is fully handicapped, that is in a wheelchair, can roll up to their kitchen sink, can roll into their shower.

147
00:13:41,882 --> 00:13:44,983
[SPEAKER_02]: The way you position grab bars and different

148
00:13:46,355 --> 00:14:07,798
[SPEAKER_02]: Hardware and your bathrooms and kitchen it just set up for people with disabilities and also like audio Visual disabilities to provide within these units So there's a plan to have ten two-bedroom units also and within one of the two-bedroom units be fully cap fully handicapped accessible and That is in a six-story mid-rise building

149
00:14:08,664 --> 00:14:12,965
[SPEAKER_02]: where the majority of the ground floor is actually podium parking.

150
00:14:13,245 --> 00:14:17,586
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's kind of like one floor of parking and then five floors of residential units.

151
00:14:20,367 --> 00:14:25,328
[SPEAKER_02]: Phase two would be 40 deeply affordable family housing units.

152
00:14:26,008 --> 00:14:30,049
[SPEAKER_02]: With construction, all goes well would be anticipated to start the end of 2025, early 2026.

153
00:14:30,089 --> 00:14:31,010
[SPEAKER_02]: 24 of the 40 units would be

154
00:14:37,608 --> 00:14:43,112
[SPEAKER_02]: and a rare elevator accessible four-story family mid runs.

155
00:14:44,313 --> 00:14:49,536
[SPEAKER_02]: And out of those 24 units, six of those would be fully handicap accessible for families.

156
00:14:49,736 --> 00:14:56,821
[SPEAKER_02]: And this type of building is a rarity, not just in Medford, it's a rarity throughout the Commonwealth, throughout the country.

157
00:14:56,921 --> 00:15:02,245
[SPEAKER_02]: Having fully handicap accessible units for families is a huge need.

158
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:10,962
[SPEAKER_02]: would also put, so there'd be 24 units in the family mid-rise, then 16 units within townhomes.

159
00:15:11,022 --> 00:15:19,965
[SPEAKER_02]: So there'd be three townhouse buildings, so three townhouse buildings with a total of 16 units, and one of those townhouse units would be fully handicap-assessable.

160
00:15:21,445 --> 00:15:28,867
[SPEAKER_02]: Every single unit on the site would be deeply affordable to households that are at or below 60% of the area median income.

161
00:15:30,108 --> 00:15:34,269
[SPEAKER_02]: And tenants, again, would pay no more than 30% of their income on rent,

162
00:15:35,168 --> 00:15:46,194
[SPEAKER_02]: And this whole redevelopment, the only thing that makes this possible is switching from what is like our public housing platform to a project-based voucher platform.

163
00:15:47,935 --> 00:15:57,079
[SPEAKER_02]: How things work is that we get through your vouchers a higher per unit subsidy than we get having it in the public housing platform.

164
00:15:57,620 --> 00:16:04,003
[SPEAKER_02]: And that just allows for better operations, maintenance, capitalizing for capital repairs,

165
00:16:04,980 --> 00:16:16,522
[SPEAKER_02]: So being able to switch from that historically underfunded state-aided portfolio to this project-based voucher platform, it's the only way we're able to do this.

166
00:16:23,883 --> 00:16:27,804
[SPEAKER_02]: So again, phase one of construction would hope to start in June of 2024.

167
00:16:28,604 --> 00:16:32,845
[SPEAKER_02]: Our architectural team is currently in the construction drawing phase.

168
00:16:34,053 --> 00:16:48,786
[SPEAKER_02]: The total development cost would be approximately $117 million, which would be funded through the 4% low-income housing tax credits, a permanent mortgage, federal and state funding, and MHA contributions.

169
00:16:48,907 --> 00:16:58,015
[SPEAKER_02]: So, you know, we pool as many resources as we have, and whatever we can get locally from the state, from the federal government, we put whatever we can into these projects.

170
00:16:59,482 --> 00:17:05,004
[SPEAKER_02]: So far, we've received a very competitive $15 million grant from the state.

171
00:17:05,385 --> 00:17:12,468
[SPEAKER_02]: And we just submitted, on Friday, another application to the state, which could possibly award up to $10.8 million.

172
00:17:14,349 --> 00:17:16,269
[SPEAKER_02]: We've also submitted for local funding.

173
00:17:16,329 --> 00:17:20,511
[SPEAKER_02]: We've submitted a MassWorks infrastructure grant application in June.

174
00:17:21,452 --> 00:17:24,433
[SPEAKER_02]: And by the end of the month, we'll be submitting what's called a home application.

175
00:17:26,557 --> 00:17:31,838
[SPEAKER_02]: Currently, we've secured 1.95 million from the Community Preservation Commission.

176
00:17:33,439 --> 00:17:42,901
[SPEAKER_02]: In this project, the city would be expected to leverage $23.70 for every $1 provided to the project.

177
00:17:42,941 --> 00:17:47,623
[SPEAKER_02]: And this is based on a $4.75 million local funding.

178
00:17:47,763 --> 00:17:52,404
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's a combination of the community preservation funding, mass works, home,

179
00:17:55,163 --> 00:18:05,532
