[SPEAKER_02]: So for the seniors to see, so right now, it's about 0.5%.

355
00:33:23,593 --> 00:33:25,175
[SPEAKER_02]: 3.5 or .4 of spaces.

356
00:33:25,755 --> 00:33:29,939
[SPEAKER_02]: It's going to be .5 per unit for the elderly, disabled.

357
00:33:30,079 --> 00:33:32,821
[SPEAKER_02]: For the family units, it's going to be one space per unit.

358
00:33:32,961 --> 00:33:34,022
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay, got it.

359
00:33:34,142 --> 00:33:38,486
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you, given the studies you've done so far, do you think a lot of that's going to end up sitting empty?

360
00:33:42,369 --> 00:33:43,410
[SPEAKER_02]: It's a great question.

361
00:33:45,212 --> 00:33:46,753
[SPEAKER_02]: I think it's adequate.

362
00:33:51,618 --> 00:33:55,980
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there too much parking, or is, because it's close to transit accessible.

363
00:33:56,820 --> 00:33:59,662
[SPEAKER_02]: For the elderly, I think we're good.

364
00:33:59,882 --> 00:34:01,343
[SPEAKER_02]: The family, you just don't know.

365
00:34:01,363 --> 00:34:06,185
[SPEAKER_02]: It depends if there's like a two bedroom, a three bedroom unit, maybe.

366
00:34:06,365 --> 00:34:07,986
[SPEAKER_02]: The household may have two cars.

367
00:34:08,026 --> 00:34:15,810
[SPEAKER_04]: So if you may be able to speak to that, Marvin, you may have some better experience with that.

368
00:34:18,071 --> 00:34:20,572
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so presently there's 34 parking spaces per 100 people.

369
00:34:21,727 --> 00:34:23,710
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay.

370
00:34:23,770 --> 00:34:24,251
[SPEAKER_09]: Good evening.

371
00:34:24,271 --> 00:34:25,552
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm Margaret Donnelly-Moran.

372
00:34:25,593 --> 00:34:27,796
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm the Housing Authority's Development Consultant.

373
00:34:30,019 --> 00:34:34,105
[SPEAKER_09]: I work through the Cambridge Housing Authority, which is the development consultant for the Medford Housing Authority.

374
00:34:34,125 --> 00:34:38,210
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm their Deputy Executive Director for Development.

375
00:34:39,749 --> 00:34:43,950
[SPEAKER_09]: In terms of parking, as I said, we have 34 parking spots now for 144.

376
00:34:44,231 --> 00:34:46,031
[SPEAKER_09]: So I think it's been underserved.

377
00:34:46,511 --> 00:34:52,193
[SPEAKER_09]: But going up to 0.5 will greatly help the elderly population and adequately meet that need.

378
00:34:52,793 --> 00:34:56,875
[SPEAKER_09]: We're doing the one space per unit for the family.

379
00:34:57,395 --> 00:34:59,416
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think, for the most part, that will be adequate.

380
00:34:59,436 --> 00:35:02,597
[SPEAKER_09]: There's a larger number of one-bedroom units as part of the 40 units.

381
00:35:03,817 --> 00:35:08,160
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think it's very clear those unit cars will have either one or no parking.

382
00:35:08,981 --> 00:35:12,884
[SPEAKER_09]: And then folks have to remember that this is deeply affordable housing.

383
00:35:12,924 --> 00:35:23,092
[SPEAKER_09]: So the average rent that a family has typically in the Medford Housing Authority portfolio is somewhere around $600 per month, which is about a $30,000 income.

384
00:35:23,132 --> 00:35:28,176
[SPEAKER_09]: So it's very hard to afford one car, let alone two or three cars per family.

385
00:35:28,596 --> 00:35:30,938
[SPEAKER_15]: And the angle I'm going at here is more so on the,

386
00:35:31,974 --> 00:35:42,101
[SPEAKER_15]: And I know this is pretty far baked, so it may be too late, but could there be more units because there are going to be a lot of empty parking spaces, right, if it's in the podium structure?

387
00:35:44,863 --> 00:35:46,324
[SPEAKER_02]: Even five affordable units is huge.

388
00:35:46,344 --> 00:35:51,768
[SPEAKER_02]: So one of the things we need to account for, too, is the visitor parking.

389
00:35:52,348 --> 00:36:01,215
[SPEAKER_02]: Also, because you do have a lot of visiting nurses here and there that come, home health aides.

390
00:36:02,469 --> 00:36:12,536
[SPEAKER_02]: So yeah, we feel that we have it lined up fairly well for what is going to be necessary on the site.

391
00:36:14,037 --> 00:36:16,458
[SPEAKER_02]: But it is a great question.

392
00:36:17,459 --> 00:36:26,625
[SPEAKER_15]: And this may be a long shot, but say you find that we have twice as much parking as we need in five or 10 years, would it be possible to renovate

393
00:36:28,120 --> 00:36:30,962
[SPEAKER_15]: a piece of that parking to add units at a later date?

394
00:36:31,022 --> 00:36:35,806
[SPEAKER_15]: Or is the construction not going to be sufficient that you could put something in that same location?

395
00:36:36,547 --> 00:36:41,051
[SPEAKER_15]: I understand that parking infrastructure looks physically different than a housing unit.

396
00:36:42,071 --> 00:36:46,815
[SPEAKER_13]: It's a tag team approach.

397
00:36:46,995 --> 00:36:48,036
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, I appreciate it.

398
00:36:48,717 --> 00:36:50,218
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't know that at this point in time

399
00:36:50,541 --> 00:36:54,963
[SPEAKER_13]: there's any consideration of any additional units on that site.

400
00:36:55,924 --> 00:37:05,129
[SPEAKER_13]: But there certainly are opportunities at other sites of the Housing Authority that would probably be more beneficial for us to explore.

401
00:37:05,369 --> 00:37:12,813
[SPEAKER_13]: Not only, as I indicated earlier, LaPree Village, but we also undertook a master plan for the 121 Riverside.

402
00:37:13,233 --> 00:37:17,315
[SPEAKER_13]: And there's a possibility right now for an additional 88 units on that site.

403
00:37:17,871 --> 00:37:26,377
[SPEAKER_13]: So I think the housing authority would look more toward that than any further expansion of Walkman Court.

404
00:37:26,397 --> 00:37:32,381
[SPEAKER_13]: Walkman Court's just over three acres, whereas Lippery Village is almost 12 acres.

405
00:37:32,581 --> 00:37:33,121
[SPEAKER_15]: Oh, for sure.

406
00:37:33,461 --> 00:37:35,683
[SPEAKER_15]: I guess I just mean within the existing structure.

407
00:37:36,423 --> 00:37:43,308
[SPEAKER_15]: If you have a parking in the podium and it's half empty all the time, it's just space that maybe could have been designed differently.

408
00:37:43,348 --> 00:37:45,790
[SPEAKER_15]: And we're seeing a lot of that in a lot of parts of the city.

409
00:37:47,267 --> 00:37:50,008
[SPEAKER_13]: At this point, I can say that we're not investigating that.

410
00:37:50,248 --> 00:37:54,330
[SPEAKER_13]: But as I said, I think there are opportunities elsewhere for that.

411
00:37:54,910 --> 00:38:03,353
[SPEAKER_13]: And as Gabe just indicated, there's a very low percentage of available parking on site for the residents who are there now.

412
00:38:03,573 --> 00:38:04,653
[SPEAKER_15]: And it's usually pretty full.

413
00:38:04,893 --> 00:38:05,093
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

414
00:38:05,273 --> 00:38:05,793
[SPEAKER_13]: Oh, yes.

415
00:38:05,813 --> 00:38:06,914
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

416
00:38:07,334 --> 00:38:07,734
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

417
00:38:08,314 --> 00:38:12,456
[SPEAKER_15]: My other question is about the shift to the project-based voucher structure.

418
00:38:14,464 --> 00:38:17,727
[SPEAKER_15]: It seems a shift in model, and I want to make sure I understand it.

419
00:38:20,069 --> 00:38:29,718
[SPEAKER_15]: Moving from, you kind of said the public housing model to the project-based vouchers model, is the property going to stay under the ownership and management of the MHA?

420
00:38:29,858 --> 00:38:31,480
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, that is a great question.

421
00:38:32,718 --> 00:38:35,959
[SPEAKER_02]: Essentially, our residents will experience no change.

422
00:38:36,079 --> 00:38:42,780
[SPEAKER_02]: Their rent remains affordable throughout construction, throughout lease up, in the new building.

423
00:38:43,220 --> 00:38:51,542
[SPEAKER_02]: And the Medford Housing Authority will still maintain, operate, manage during construction and when we're complete.

424
00:38:51,762 --> 00:38:59,443
[SPEAKER_02]: So yeah, we are gonna still maintain ownership and management operation of the development.

425
00:39:03,464 --> 00:39:10,968
[SPEAKER_09]: So the switch from public housing to the project-based voucher program is really an attempt to bring more federal resources to the project.

426
00:39:11,049 --> 00:39:13,530
[SPEAKER_09]: And I'll speak to the salt and salt property first.

427
00:39:14,350 --> 00:39:26,357
[SPEAKER_09]: The housing authority went through a process with HUD where submitted a disposition application because the renovation needs were so in excess of what any resource that the housing authority had access to.

428
00:39:26,977 --> 00:39:31,720
[SPEAKER_09]: And in doing that, that application and being successful with it, the housing authority was able to

429
00:39:32,412 --> 00:39:42,326
[SPEAKER_09]: We see from HUD 200 project-based vouchers that are being used now at Salt Sol to fund the renovation there and keep the units deeply affordable.

430
00:39:42,707 --> 00:39:46,713
[SPEAKER_09]: That added to the housing authority and to the Medford community somewhere around $3.6 million of

431
00:39:48,614 --> 00:39:53,936
[SPEAKER_09]: annual increase in income that the housing authority has been able to reinvest in that property.

432
00:39:54,576 --> 00:40:08,842
[SPEAKER_09]: And we're following that model to a certain extent at Waukland Court, where we are actually switching it from state public housing to federal public housing, and then going through a process that HUD has created to move it into the project-based vouchers.

433
00:40:09,482 --> 00:40:11,843
[SPEAKER_09]: Because as Gabe said, that income

434
00:40:12,716 --> 00:40:25,406
[SPEAKER_09]: is much higher and more predictable than what we received under the public housing program, and even much more significant than what the housing authorities receive under state public housing.

435
00:40:25,446 --> 00:40:28,028
[SPEAKER_09]: So the conversion to federal is really key.

436
00:40:28,389 --> 00:40:35,114
[SPEAKER_09]: The other piece that is being used at both at Salt and Stone and Wakling Court is low-income housing tax credits.

437
00:40:35,835 --> 00:40:38,537
[SPEAKER_09]: And the housing authority maintains the ownership of the land

438
00:40:39,350 --> 00:41:00,682
[SPEAKER_09]: but uses the really one tool that HUD has that provides more meaningful resources for affordable housing preservation and development, the low-income housing tax credit, which incentivizes private folks to invest in affordable housing, and their return is a tax credit from the federal government.

439
00:41:01,183 --> 00:41:08,747
[SPEAKER_09]: And we've been able to raise about $60 million of tax credits for Salt and Stall, and it will be close to the same amount for Waukland Court,

440
00:41:09,201 --> 00:41:14,743
[SPEAKER_09]: where all the housing authority is promising to do is keep it as affordable housing check.

441
00:41:15,084 --> 00:41:22,947
[SPEAKER_09]: We do that day in and day out, and to continue to operate it consistent with the program requirements that we have.

442
00:41:23,387 --> 00:41:27,569
[SPEAKER_09]: And over the time, they will get their return through the tax credit.

443
00:41:27,869 --> 00:41:35,012
[SPEAKER_09]: But it is a way to bring the funds that the housing authority needs to make these deep renovations or redevelopments to the equation.

444
00:41:35,032 --> 00:41:36,773
[SPEAKER_09]: But as part of that transaction,

445
00:41:37,348 --> 00:41:49,018
[SPEAKER_09]: housing authority maintains ownership of the land, but the property goes and is held by a limited liability corporation that has the private investor involved because that's the only way that they can get the tax credit.

446
00:41:49,379 --> 00:41:58,307
[SPEAKER_09]: So there's a legal piece that happens that allows the investor to get their tax credits, allows the housing authority to continue to be the manager

447
00:41:59,172 --> 00:42:16,797
[SPEAKER_09]: maintainer and owner of the land of the property and then after the 15 years when the tax credit investor has gotten their full tax credits, the property actually is, you know, is goes back to the housing authority to a transaction so Cambridge Housing Authority has kind of set the model for this.

448
00:42:17,377 --> 00:42:18,878
[SPEAKER_09]: going back over 20 years.

449
00:42:18,998 --> 00:42:25,462
[SPEAKER_09]: And we've seen properties go through that entire cycle where we've brought in a low-income housing tax credit investor.

450
00:42:25,482 --> 00:42:26,763
[SPEAKER_09]: They've given us a lot of money.

451
00:42:26,803 --> 00:42:28,925
[SPEAKER_09]: We've reinvested that into the property.

452
00:42:29,305 --> 00:42:36,750
[SPEAKER_09]: And at the end of that 15-year period, those units, that building comes back to 100% control of the housing authority.

453
00:42:37,130 --> 00:42:42,053
[SPEAKER_09]: But throughout that 15-year process, the Cambridge Housing Authority, in this case, the Medford Housing Authority,

454
00:42:42,593 --> 00:42:52,278
[SPEAKER_09]: has all the protections of being the day-to-day manager of the property, as well as the holder of the ground lease, as well as other key terms and provisions within the documents.

455
00:42:53,419 --> 00:42:54,319
[SPEAKER_15]: Thanks for explaining it.

456
00:42:54,359 --> 00:43:01,663
[SPEAKER_15]: I think I finally understand something that I had heard and was kind of studying for a long time.

457
00:43:01,683 --> 00:43:07,186
[SPEAKER_15]: I know this is completely out of your control, but that seems like a really convoluted way to solve for not funding public housing.

458
00:43:08,505 --> 00:43:09,926
[SPEAKER_09]: I always usually say that.

459
00:43:10,026 --> 00:43:12,928
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not the way I would design it.

460
00:43:12,988 --> 00:43:24,455
[SPEAKER_09]: I've been doing affordable housing development in the public housing arena for over 30 years, and this is the most inefficient way to deliver resources to a community.

461
00:43:24,495 --> 00:43:37,342
[SPEAKER_09]: But unfortunately, it really is the only way that we can, as a housing authority, generate any kind of access to any meaningful capital to kind of do what's absolutely needed, which is protect and preserve the resources that we have and then

462
00:43:37,870 --> 00:43:46,454
[SPEAKER_09]: look to expand the resources in the way that the MHA is doing with the 22 new units at Salt and Stall, but also the 98 new units at Waukling.

463
00:43:47,534 --> 00:43:52,396
[SPEAKER_15]: I may just repeat it, and I don't want to take too much more time on it, just so I'm not completely off point.

464
00:43:52,456 --> 00:44:03,781
[SPEAKER_15]: Basically, federal government created a tax credit that only private investors can get for affordable housing, and the only way for public housing to access it is to create a legal entity to allow someone to privately invest to get the public money.

465
00:44:03,801 --> 00:44:04,321
[SPEAKER_04]: You are good.

466
00:44:05,222 --> 00:44:05,382
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

467
00:44:08,176 --> 00:44:09,257
[SPEAKER_15]: That's like four steps.

468
00:44:09,597 --> 00:44:10,538
[SPEAKER_15]: That could be one step.

469
00:44:10,638 --> 00:44:16,143
[SPEAKER_09]: And then it reverts back to the ownership at the end of the back to the housing authority.

470
00:44:16,523 --> 00:44:16,803
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay.

471
00:44:16,884 --> 00:44:17,464
[SPEAKER_09]: And guess what?

472
00:44:17,924 --> 00:44:18,665
[SPEAKER_09]: You could do it again.

473
00:44:18,685 --> 00:44:20,226
[SPEAKER_15]: Right?

474
00:44:20,266 --> 00:44:21,127
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, yeah, great.

475
00:44:21,307 --> 00:44:26,111
[SPEAKER_15]: You know, I'm sure that's Yeah, I the word inefficient certainly comes to mind.

476
00:44:26,772 --> 00:44:32,777
[SPEAKER_15]: But, you know, glad it's been successful in Cambridge, for what it is.

477
00:44:32,837 --> 00:44:33,758
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, in Cambridge,

478
00:44:34,314 --> 00:44:42,117
[SPEAKER_09]: So I mentioned about $60 million at Salt-N-Salt will be equivalent, plus or minus, at Walkman.

479
00:44:42,137 --> 00:44:48,120
[SPEAKER_09]: That's $120 million of economic resources coming to Medford.

480
00:44:48,160 --> 00:44:52,622
[SPEAKER_09]: In Cambridge, we're close to now about $450 million, just since 2010.

481
00:44:53,842 --> 00:44:57,063
[SPEAKER_09]: And that's just not money we would be able to access.

482
00:44:57,083 --> 00:45:01,325
[SPEAKER_09]: And we've used that money in Cambridge to do about $650 million of construction.

483
00:45:01,345 --> 00:45:03,306
[SPEAKER_09]: Again, vitally needed because we had units

484
00:45:04,143 --> 00:45:07,604
[SPEAKER_09]: in as dire condition as what the MHA has.

485
00:45:07,784 --> 00:45:14,706
[SPEAKER_09]: And it's really a chance to reset the housing and really restore it as well.

486
00:45:14,726 --> 00:45:17,446
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's a real wonderful outcome.

487
00:45:17,466 --> 00:45:18,007
[SPEAKER_09]: All right.

488
00:45:18,127 --> 00:45:21,427
[SPEAKER_15]: I think the last three short things I can get to really quickly.

489
00:45:22,648 --> 00:45:31,190
[SPEAKER_15]: You already answered this the last time we had a meeting about this, but everyone who is in Wakling Court who wants to come back is able to come back, correct?

490
00:45:32,711 --> 00:45:33,511
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, exactly.

491
00:45:33,571 --> 00:45:37,813
[SPEAKER_02]: So every existing resident has what's called the right to return.

492
00:45:37,873 --> 00:45:43,415
[SPEAKER_02]: So every existing resident walking court will have the right to return to the new mid-rise building.

493
00:45:44,115 --> 00:45:53,158
[SPEAKER_15]: And does this low-income tax credit structure or the project-based voucher structure change eligibility for residents or change how much they're paying compared to what they pay now?

494
00:45:53,878 --> 00:45:57,599
[SPEAKER_09]: So the rent structure is still based on percentage of income.

495
00:45:57,619 --> 00:45:58,100
[SPEAKER_09]: So it's 30% of the

496
00:46:00,606 --> 00:46:03,748
[SPEAKER_09]: income which is comparable to what it is on the state public housing side.

497
00:46:03,788 --> 00:46:04,969
[SPEAKER_09]: There's some slight differences.

498
00:46:05,389 --> 00:46:14,254
[SPEAKER_09]: For many residents, I think they'll actually see a small decrease in rent because there's a little extra deductions on the federal side that exist on the state side.

499
00:46:14,274 --> 00:46:29,403
[SPEAKER_09]: There are a few instances where there will be some residents who have an exclusion of earned income that we will work with to mitigate or lessen the increase that they might face, but it's literally a handful of folks.

500
00:46:30,208 --> 00:46:32,629
[SPEAKER_09]: But programmatically, it's very much the same.

501
00:46:33,129 --> 00:46:37,511
[SPEAKER_09]: The eligibility overall, you know, everybody will have the right to return.

502
00:46:37,531 --> 00:46:48,735
[SPEAKER_09]: If for some reason they're over income, then the housing authority just would not take the tax credits in that unit so that we would fulfill the commitment made to the residents.

503
00:46:49,195 --> 00:46:54,657
[SPEAKER_09]: And then going forward, the eligibility is 60% of area median income, which is slightly lower, I think, right now.

504
00:46:54,677 --> 00:46:56,238
[SPEAKER_09]: Is it 80% for state housing?

505
00:47:00,038 --> 00:47:05,981
[SPEAKER_09]: So the ban will go slightly down, but that's consistent with the low-income housing tax credit requirements.

506
00:47:06,041 --> 00:47:06,761
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay, got it.

507
00:47:07,101 --> 00:47:11,123
[SPEAKER_15]: I think that's it for now.

508
00:47:11,143 --> 00:47:12,024
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, I appreciate it.

509
00:47:12,804 --> 00:47:13,064
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

510
00:47:13,104 --> 00:47:13,745
[SPEAKER_17]: Councilor Hollis.

511
00:47:16,426 --> 00:47:17,026
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you so much.

512
00:47:17,647 --> 00:47:18,987
[SPEAKER_08]: Really appreciate the presentation.

513
00:47:19,007 --> 00:47:26,991
[SPEAKER_08]: As in the previous times, this project has come before the council into a really compelling picture, and I appreciate the presentation.

514
00:47:27,011 --> 00:47:28,492
[SPEAKER_08]: I think it helps

515
00:47:29,307 --> 00:47:41,955
[SPEAKER_08]: clarify it helps me visualize why this is a really good site to invest in to put more affordable housing in to put more dense affordable housing in, especially now that we have even more transit along this corridor.

516
00:47:44,245 --> 00:47:52,487
[SPEAKER_08]: And of course, there's not many opportunities that as a community, we get to make a double digit percentage leap towards our sustainable unit goals as a city.

517
00:47:53,627 --> 00:47:55,127
[SPEAKER_08]: So that's extremely exciting.

518
00:47:55,167 --> 00:48:02,849
[SPEAKER_08]: And I appreciate also the discussion of like, can we be doing even better on the land that we have an opportunity to redevelop right now?

519
00:48:03,429 --> 00:48:04,409
[SPEAKER_08]: So thank you so much for that.

520
00:48:06,750 --> 00:48:12,131
[SPEAKER_08]: Since we were just talking about AMI, I always wanna make sure that I'm understanding those distinctions just a little more clearly.

521
00:48:13,480 --> 00:48:17,802
[SPEAKER_08]: And I know in the presentation you just mentioned, it's going to be at or below 60%.

522
00:48:17,842 --> 00:48:32,870
[SPEAKER_08]: AMI, I was curious if there's a further breakdown, if it's like X many units at 30% and then at 60%, or is that everybody's going to be at or below 60% and... Yeah, this is totally inside baseball, but I appreciate the question.

523
00:48:33,190 --> 00:48:41,995
[SPEAKER_09]: So under the qualified allocation plan that the state sets up for handling how low income housing tax credit projects work, today we have a requirement that

524
00:48:42,557 --> 00:48:50,763
[SPEAKER_09]: a minimum of 13% of the units be set aside for folks who are at 30% of area median income or lower.

525
00:48:50,803 --> 00:49:00,449
[SPEAKER_09]: So if you were a typical developer, not a public housing agency, your requirement would be 13% of your total units, and you would pretty much adhere to that.

526
00:49:01,130 --> 00:49:04,052
[SPEAKER_09]: But the housing authority, you'll be on a wait list.

527
00:49:04,092 --> 00:49:06,593
[SPEAKER_09]: You'll come in based on the date of your application.

528
00:49:06,633 --> 00:49:08,274
[SPEAKER_09]: You could be at 60%, you could be at 0%,

529
00:49:09,655 --> 00:49:14,839
[SPEAKER_09]: you'll get housed irrespective of that provided, of course, we meet that 13% requirement.

530
00:49:15,560 --> 00:49:24,728
[SPEAKER_09]: What I've found my many years working with the housing authorities, most applicants on the housing authorities waiting list are below 30% of area median income.

531
00:49:25,168 --> 00:49:28,951
[SPEAKER_09]: So our development will be typically more to meeting the 30% requirement.

532
00:49:31,476 --> 00:49:32,537
[SPEAKER_09]: rather than the 60% number.

533
00:49:32,557 --> 00:49:43,506
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, we do get folks who are between 40 and 50%, they'll be housed as well, because they'll be coming up on the waiting list, but the majority of the folks will actually be 30% of area median income or below.

534
00:49:44,067 --> 00:49:44,647
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, thank you.

535
00:49:44,687 --> 00:49:54,475
[SPEAKER_08]: And just to check my understanding and also to check my hearing, because the acoustics in here are hard, what I'm hearing is you take people off of the queue, and usually that results in more of a shift towards the AMI-30.

536
00:49:54,495 --> 00:49:57,938
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, just because that's what was reflected on the waiting list.

537
00:49:58,421 --> 00:49:58,601
[SPEAKER_08]: I agree.

538
00:49:58,881 --> 00:49:59,121
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

539
00:49:59,141 --> 00:49:59,762
[SPEAKER_08]: I appreciate that.

540
00:50:00,282 --> 00:50:02,303
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks so much.

541
00:50:03,704 --> 00:50:06,725
[SPEAKER_17]: We'll go to Councilor Carviello on Zoom.

542
00:50:06,765 --> 00:50:07,485
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Madam President.

543
00:50:08,726 --> 00:50:09,886
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for the presentation.

544
00:50:09,906 --> 00:50:12,188
[SPEAKER_10]: It was, as always, very thorough.

545
00:50:13,168 --> 00:50:19,971
[SPEAKER_10]: Probably the most amount of concern that I was hearing from residents were for the two six-story buildings.

546
00:50:21,192 --> 00:50:26,274
[SPEAKER_10]: They were somewhat concerned about pollution from the train and other issues.

547
00:50:26,714 --> 00:50:27,775
[SPEAKER_10]: How are we addressing that?

548
00:50:30,763 --> 00:50:32,424
[SPEAKER_17]: said pollution from the train, correct?

549
00:50:32,444 --> 00:50:35,585
[SPEAKER_17]: The height of the buildings and the potential pollution from the train.

550
00:50:35,605 --> 00:50:41,348
[SPEAKER_10]: The six-story height, that seems to be a big concern that I've heard from a lot of residents.

551
00:50:42,709 --> 00:50:44,510
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, great question.

552
00:50:45,330 --> 00:50:59,117
[SPEAKER_02]: So the six-story height, as we spoke about earlier, to try to maintain a fair amount of landscape, open, usable space,

553
00:51:00,234 --> 00:51:04,418
[SPEAKER_02]: to go a little, so the higher you go, the more you can shrink that building footprint.

554
00:51:05,339 --> 00:51:13,508
[SPEAKER_02]: And we scaled the site back again towards the southern part of the site where across the tracks there's a mid-rise building.

555
00:51:13,528 --> 00:51:20,955
[SPEAKER_02]: So our building will be right along the same height as the building across the train tracks.

556
00:51:22,577 --> 00:51:23,278
[SPEAKER_02]: In terms of

557
00:51:24,537 --> 00:51:26,639
[SPEAKER_02]: pollution from the train.

558
00:51:27,219 --> 00:51:29,000
[SPEAKER_02]: We have existing structures.

559
00:51:29,080 --> 00:51:38,005
[SPEAKER_02]: So three of our nine residential buildings are actually within the proximity or even closer than some of the new units at the mid-rise will be.

560
00:51:38,045 --> 00:51:43,249
[SPEAKER_02]: So at a minimum, we need to have a 30 foot setback from the train tracks.

561
00:51:44,329 --> 00:51:49,613
[SPEAKER_02]: So we have existing units that are right now within that footprint.

562
00:51:50,173 --> 00:51:51,514
[SPEAKER_02]: And as I stated before,

563
00:51:52,985 --> 00:51:55,726
[SPEAKER_02]: regarding acoustical stuff like that.

564
00:51:55,786 --> 00:52:05,108
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I'm sorry, it was 20, a minimum of 22 feet from, yeah, current buildings, yeah, within the footprint that are right now within 22 feet of the train tracks.

565
00:52:05,488 --> 00:52:08,868
[SPEAKER_02]: The new structures need to be a minimum of 30 feet from the train tracks.

566
00:52:10,229 --> 00:52:16,550
[SPEAKER_10]: Would it be possible to put a sound barrier up there, like a sound wall to play some of the noise too, also?

567
00:52:18,681 --> 00:52:32,452
[SPEAKER_02]: That is something that we have investigated, but I know dealing with the MBTA and building anything within or with on their property lines is, I know historically is a big issue.

568
00:52:32,512 --> 00:52:34,333
[SPEAKER_02]: I can't speak to that at all.

569
00:52:34,473 --> 00:52:43,360
[SPEAKER_09]: So, I mean, the design of the building itself will be done to really handle the noise so that the noise inside the building will be kept to

570
00:52:43,900 --> 00:52:48,663
[SPEAKER_09]: well below any kind of measurable standard in terms of requirements.

571
00:52:49,224 --> 00:52:56,429
[SPEAKER_09]: Very different from the leaky, not weather tight, not very good window buildings that we have in place.

572
00:52:56,449 --> 00:52:59,711
[SPEAKER_09]: So the windows will be triple glazed, there'll be added insulation.

573
00:53:00,151 --> 00:53:09,658
[SPEAKER_09]: The actual way the building is structured on site, most of it does not face direct onto the train, so it provides for a little bit of a bounce off of the noise.

574
00:53:10,820 --> 00:53:31,997
[SPEAKER_09]: with the way that the architect has positioned it, but the buildings and the materials that are gonna be used are gonna really mitigate less than the noise, certainly well below any kind of standard and certainly well above what residents currently experience in the three buildings that are closest there.

575
00:53:32,792 --> 00:53:45,637
[SPEAKER_09]: And then the ventilation system, you know, it will actually have a ventilation system that works, which is something that the existing buildings don't have, and a cooling system as well.

576
00:53:46,237 --> 00:53:53,880
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think that will really enhance the quality of the air and provide healthier air coming in and out of the buildings than what the residents currently experience.

577
00:53:56,001 --> 00:53:56,661
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you very much.

578
00:53:58,261 --> 00:53:59,062
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Councilor Perriello.

579
00:54:00,280 --> 00:54:03,923
[SPEAKER_03]: So it sounds like essentially you've built the sound barrier into the building, into the walls.

580
00:54:04,643 --> 00:54:15,732
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, that was a major question that I had received from a lot of folks and it's, I think, comforting to know about the 30 foot setback.

581
00:54:17,413 --> 00:54:26,018
[SPEAKER_03]: And I guess the second part of what Councillor Caravella was saying was about air quality and insulation.

582
00:54:26,499 --> 00:54:33,884
[SPEAKER_03]: And if you could speak a little bit to that as well and to what you guys are doing to mitigate that, that'd be super helpful.

583
00:54:34,724 --> 00:54:40,568
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, just as Margaret stated, so right now the buildings, one of the biggest complaints we get from residents

584
00:54:41,866 --> 00:54:46,389
[SPEAKER_02]: is sound through units that their existing units are not insulated well.

585
00:54:47,190 --> 00:55:10,647
[SPEAKER_02]: The exterior, just the way buildings are built now, and especially with how we're gonna be building this new mid-rise building, compared to how things are built in 1960s, the residents will see an amazing increase in the air quality within their units through ventilation, through, as Margaret stated, we're providing central air conditioning, central heating to the building.

586
00:55:12,827 --> 00:55:32,007
[SPEAKER_02]: So just through those state-of-the-art ventilation, the triple glazed windows, better insulation, the existing residents now, the quality of air comfort within these new buildings is going to be night and day compared to what they're experiencing now in the existing structures.

587
00:55:32,208 --> 00:55:34,310
[SPEAKER_03]: So those things are things that don't exist now?

588
00:55:34,730 --> 00:55:35,811
[SPEAKER_03]: within the current structure.

589
00:55:36,191 --> 00:55:40,893
[SPEAKER_03]: And so a lot of, you know, what folks living there might be doing today, right?

590
00:55:40,993 --> 00:55:48,236
[SPEAKER_03]: Like opening the windows, that behavior will probably shift with the new ventilation and AC coming in.

591
00:55:48,557 --> 00:55:49,017
[SPEAKER_02]: Exactly.

592
00:55:50,577 --> 00:55:55,560
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, there will be operable windows in the units, but yes, they'll be able to have

593
00:55:57,298 --> 00:56:04,703
[SPEAKER_02]: the type of system we're providing, they could in April, if they wanna cool their unit down a bit, they can do that.

594
00:56:04,783 --> 00:56:07,545
[SPEAKER_02]: These new systems, yeah, they're pretty amazing.

595
00:56:07,585 --> 00:56:14,590
[SPEAKER_02]: So the resident next door could turn the heat on if they're cool, resident next door if they're hot, they can cool their unit down.

596
00:56:14,690 --> 00:56:22,635
[SPEAKER_02]: So yeah, the comfort that the residents are gonna experience is night and day compared to what they have right now.

597
00:56:23,002 --> 00:56:24,504
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm glad to hear that.

598
00:56:25,084 --> 00:56:35,156
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's no surprise that a lot of us have heard a lot of different concerns from folks living in the area, and I think it's comforting to hear that.

599
00:56:35,276 --> 00:56:38,360
[SPEAKER_03]: And I do really want to thank your hard work on a project that

600
00:56:38,840 --> 00:56:47,542
[SPEAKER_03]: I think Councillor Collins made the point that it's like, it's a double digit percentage shift towards our goal, which is, you know, our city desperately needs to meet.

601
00:56:47,802 --> 00:56:50,583
[SPEAKER_03]: And so I think there's a lot of promising things about this project.

602
00:56:50,683 --> 00:56:52,824
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sure there's a lot of questions in the audience as well.

603
00:56:52,864 --> 00:56:57,945
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it'd be great to, you know, through the chair, make this a forum.

604
00:56:58,485 --> 00:57:00,266
[SPEAKER_03]: But I appreciate your work on this.

605
00:57:00,406 --> 00:57:00,726
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

606
00:57:00,946 --> 00:57:01,326
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

