01:00:53,261 --> 01:00:54,561
[SPEAKER_16]: I am familiar with the site.

659
01:00:55,647 --> 01:01:01,590
[SPEAKER_16]: I think a couple of other things here that I will rephrase those questions, but first a couple of concerns.

660
01:01:02,171 --> 01:01:06,973
[SPEAKER_16]: One is I think it's not just the neighborhood, it's a little broader than that.

661
01:01:08,194 --> 01:01:13,897
[SPEAKER_16]: It's not just the residents and the neighborhood, but I think the ripples of impact go beyond that.

662
01:01:14,798 --> 01:01:19,781
[SPEAKER_16]: Recently, the city went through a long process of developing a comprehensive plan.

663
01:01:20,801 --> 01:01:23,663
[SPEAKER_16]: Among the major goals of that plan

664
01:01:24,478 --> 01:01:37,745
[SPEAKER_16]: we're preserving and enhancing tree canopy, climate change resilience, walkable, affordable neighborhoods, a whole host of items.

665
01:01:38,165 --> 01:01:46,950
[SPEAKER_16]: Since that plan was approved last fall, I think, I'm not sure a lot of progress has been made, but there's a lot on the agenda in Bedford.

666
01:01:48,791 --> 01:01:50,592
[SPEAKER_16]: For that, is this on?

667
01:01:50,612 --> 01:01:51,052
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm sorry.

668
01:01:51,412 --> 01:01:51,732
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay.

669
01:01:52,713 --> 01:01:53,273
[SPEAKER_16]: Doesn't sound like it.

670
01:01:53,668 --> 01:01:54,148
[SPEAKER_16]: It's so good.

671
01:01:56,030 --> 01:01:58,612
[SPEAKER_16]: So a couple of questions through the chair.

672
01:01:58,772 --> 01:02:06,519
[SPEAKER_16]: I'd like to know the current percentage of green space on the site and what the percentage of green space will be after the proposed development.

673
01:02:07,159 --> 01:02:07,960
[SPEAKER_16]: That's number one.

674
01:02:09,381 --> 01:02:11,823
[SPEAKER_16]: There are a number of 60 or 70 year old trees.

675
01:02:11,883 --> 01:02:13,805
[SPEAKER_16]: A lot's been talked about that.

676
01:02:14,405 --> 01:02:16,867
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't think anybody in this room is going to be here in 70 years.

677
01:02:17,768 --> 01:02:19,830
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, maybe some people will be, but not very many.

678
01:02:19,850 --> 01:02:22,752
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, you'll be here in 70 years, sorry.

679
01:02:23,279 --> 01:02:26,881
[SPEAKER_16]: I won't, I'm 72, so I qualify for housing here, I guess.

680
01:02:27,542 --> 01:02:32,184
[SPEAKER_16]: I'd like to know what the plans are for tree planting.

681
01:02:32,304 --> 01:02:35,686
[SPEAKER_16]: I would strongly suggest that it be enhanced.

682
01:02:35,806 --> 01:02:38,968
[SPEAKER_16]: This is an opportunity to do the right thing.

683
01:02:39,849 --> 01:02:40,889
[SPEAKER_16]: That's the second question.

684
01:02:40,909 --> 01:02:50,275
[SPEAKER_16]: The exact plan for tree planting, there's been some references to landscaping, although the word trees does not appear in this document from what I can see.

685
01:02:51,490 --> 01:02:53,872
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm certainly concerned about the through traffic.

686
01:02:53,912 --> 01:02:54,893
[SPEAKER_16]: I think we're naive.

687
01:02:55,093 --> 01:02:57,195
[SPEAKER_16]: We think that this has become a cut through.

688
01:02:58,096 --> 01:03:06,603
[SPEAKER_16]: Traffic has, as people have referred to, has increased remarkably in Medford, and that process seems to have accelerated in the last five years.

689
01:03:07,704 --> 01:03:10,026
[SPEAKER_16]: I live not far from High Street.

690
01:03:10,467 --> 01:03:11,748
[SPEAKER_16]: High Street is to be avoided.

691
01:03:12,389 --> 01:03:14,370
[SPEAKER_16]: Woburn Street, much busier.

692
01:03:15,411 --> 01:03:17,033
[SPEAKER_16]: Auburn Street, that whole

693
01:03:17,870 --> 01:03:21,413
[SPEAKER_16]: area down there is a bit of a traffic nightmare under the best of circumstances.

694
01:03:21,674 --> 01:03:33,905
[SPEAKER_16]: So I think that's, you know, people use these apps like Waze and basically Waze will send you where they think the traffic isn't right through residential neighborhoods.

695
01:03:33,925 --> 01:03:35,647
[SPEAKER_16]: It's been roundly criticized for that.

696
01:03:37,307 --> 01:03:48,175
[SPEAKER_16]: Also would like to know if these are going to be LEED buildings at some level, gold, silver, I doubt platinum, but that would be certainly a big, big plus.

697
01:03:49,255 --> 01:03:53,899
[SPEAKER_16]: Also would like to know if you're going to have solar panels on top.

698
01:03:54,359 --> 01:03:55,660
[SPEAKER_16]: We have them on the library.

699
01:03:56,661 --> 01:03:59,062
[SPEAKER_16]: Supposedly we have them on the DPW building.

700
01:03:59,102 --> 01:04:05,447
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm not sure that's actually happened yet, but given the footprints of these buildings, given their height,

701
01:04:06,005 --> 01:04:08,587
[SPEAKER_16]: They're excellent candidate for solar panels.

702
01:04:08,787 --> 01:04:10,468
[SPEAKER_16]: And I hope that's part of the plan.

703
01:04:10,548 --> 01:04:12,890
[SPEAKER_16]: So I'd appreciate some answers to these questions.

704
01:04:13,330 --> 01:04:13,490
[SPEAKER_17]: Sure.

705
01:04:13,590 --> 01:04:14,471
[SPEAKER_17]: I can take the solar one.

706
01:04:14,491 --> 01:04:21,296
[SPEAKER_17]: So we do, we have the solar ordinance that was established in the city that buildings that it's a 10 units or more, 10,000 square feet or more.

707
01:04:21,316 --> 01:04:25,439
[SPEAKER_17]: They have to be assessed for solar energy to see if solar energy can apply.

708
01:04:25,459 --> 01:04:27,720
[SPEAKER_17]: If it can be applied, it has to have a coverage of at least 50%.

709
01:04:27,960 --> 01:04:31,343
[SPEAKER_17]: And Gabe did say that that's something that they're aware of and working with.

710
01:04:31,443 --> 01:04:33,124
[SPEAKER_16]: So I'm sorry, I don't understand that.

711
01:04:33,552 --> 01:04:38,075
[SPEAKER_16]: Does that mean the buildings have to be solar ready, or does it mean that they have to have solar panels?

712
01:04:38,375 --> 01:04:43,158
[SPEAKER_17]: If they are assessed as a good candidate, I'd have to look at the exact wording.

713
01:04:43,538 --> 01:04:58,468
[SPEAKER_16]: If they can actually even put solar, then they have to have at least- Well, then my follow-up question to the proponents here is whether that assessment has been made and whether they plan, because if you don't plan it now, you're never going to get them, if they plan to put solar panels on these buildings.

714
01:04:59,192 --> 01:05:02,636
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, I think, yeah, they did say that they're working with that.

715
01:05:02,656 --> 01:05:04,238
[SPEAKER_16]: So we can expect solar panels?

716
01:05:05,079 --> 01:05:05,280
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes.

717
01:05:06,581 --> 01:05:08,664
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay, I'll take the word for it.

718
01:05:09,865 --> 01:05:11,828
[SPEAKER_16]: So my other questions.

719
01:05:12,008 --> 01:05:16,694
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, if you want to address as far as the treaties and then LEED certification.

720
01:05:18,317 --> 01:05:19,078
[SPEAKER_17]: Okay, you were about to.

721
01:05:19,498 --> 01:05:20,319
[SPEAKER_17]: I was going off memory.

722
01:05:20,339 --> 01:05:21,059
[SPEAKER_02]: I think I got lost on that.

723
01:05:21,079 --> 01:05:22,300
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's start with the trees.

724
01:05:22,400 --> 01:05:23,962
[SPEAKER_02]: So we've hired an arborist.

725
01:05:25,063 --> 01:05:29,106
[SPEAKER_02]: There's currently 52 trees on site.

726
01:05:30,387 --> 01:05:45,099
[SPEAKER_02]: At the end of the development, there'll be at least 52, at least 52 trees remaining on, not the existing trees, but there will be a planting plan, landscape plan of 52 trees on the site.

727
01:05:45,561 --> 01:05:55,844
[SPEAKER_02]: We're trying to save as many trees as we can along the perimeter that, you know, on our shared property lines, but the trees that are in the middle of this site are going to be tough to save.

728
01:05:56,345 --> 01:06:03,247
[SPEAKER_02]: And we're, the plan is to replace those trees with native species, as big of caliber trees as we can afford.

729
01:06:03,267 --> 01:06:04,027
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, maybe.

730
01:06:04,067 --> 01:06:04,247
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

731
01:06:04,507 --> 01:06:09,489
[SPEAKER_17]: I think I'm probably trying to read Tom's mind because I'm sure, as you know, a new tree is not equivalent to an old tree.

732
01:06:09,629 --> 01:06:12,630
[SPEAKER_17]: So same number of trees doesn't necessarily mean the same.

733
01:06:13,423 --> 01:06:14,264
[SPEAKER_17]: beneficial impacts.

734
01:06:14,404 --> 01:06:22,811
[SPEAKER_02]: Right, of course, but with with new trees and how that if you have a good landscape architect, locations of trees, the medium they're planted in.

735
01:06:24,873 --> 01:06:30,238
[SPEAKER_02]: I like to tell people I was involved right down the street, the Cape, the redevelopment of the Cape and Cord property in Somerville.

736
01:06:31,939 --> 01:06:37,263
[SPEAKER_02]: And we put in decent sized caliber trees, they're probably 10 foot trees within

737
01:06:39,210 --> 01:06:44,192
[SPEAKER_02]: four years, it is amazing how the growth, they look like fully mature trees in four years.

738
01:06:44,273 --> 01:06:52,116
[SPEAKER_02]: So just making sure that the landscape architect puts the right species of trees in that are native, that will thrive in the conditions that we put them in.

739
01:06:53,237 --> 01:07:03,142
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, they're not huge 40-year-old trees that are off the bat, but if they're done correctly, the rate of growth is significant and can have a really big impact.

740
01:07:05,774 --> 01:07:08,295
[SPEAKER_02]: You wanna answer the question about percentages if we have that?

741
01:07:08,615 --> 01:07:16,776
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, so in terms of open space, right now there's 49,000 square feet of open space, and there'll be 30,000 square feet of open space.

742
01:07:17,696 --> 01:07:28,098
[SPEAKER_09]: Again, we really try to balance with the podium parking, the ability to provide open space, but with the increase in the number of units, there is a decrease in the open space.

743
01:07:28,959 --> 01:07:31,259
[SPEAKER_09]: In terms of the LEED certification,

744
01:07:32,152 --> 01:07:41,614
[SPEAKER_09]: We're going after what's called the Green Community Certification, which is much more suitable for multifamily housing and has been around really for over a decade.

745
01:07:42,475 --> 01:07:52,857
[SPEAKER_09]: And the standard would be kind of what we define it as equivalent to either silver or gold leads, leads being much more suitable for commercial type of buildings.

746
01:07:52,917 --> 01:08:00,539
[SPEAKER_09]: But the Green Communities Certification is very robust and requires a lot of sustainable and resiliency measures.

747
01:08:01,534 --> 01:08:03,755
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm trying to think what was the last question.

748
01:08:07,397 --> 01:08:29,026
[SPEAKER_02]: And I'd like to stress, too, that the new, open, usable landscape space is going to be a lot more accessible, easier to use for our elderly and disabled residents, where right now we have, it's a nice site, but there's just like just unusable lawn spaces where there's no pathways through them.

749
01:08:29,407 --> 01:08:30,067
[SPEAKER_02]: They're really not,

750
01:08:30,897 --> 01:08:39,043
[SPEAKER_02]: they're really not used, they look nice, but we're looking to create actually nice outdoor spaces that can be easily usable.

751
01:08:39,604 --> 01:08:45,528
[SPEAKER_09]: Including like a circular walkway that folks can go out and get exercise.

752
01:08:45,929 --> 01:08:52,534
[SPEAKER_09]: I think the last question that was on my list was around through traffic, which I think we covered, which is, you know, we're following the direction of the fire department.

753
01:08:52,574 --> 01:08:55,936
[SPEAKER_09]: I think we definitely have traffic calming measures in

754
01:08:57,413 --> 01:09:10,302
[SPEAKER_09]: the scope of work and I think the discussion on whether a portion of the road will be one way or not is something that we'll be taking our guidance from city staff and particularly the emergency service provisions or the departments of the city.

755
01:09:11,183 --> 01:09:27,847
[SPEAKER_02]: looking at different options too, like having, like we have now two separate entrances, like what if you had just an entrance for the family site, a separate entrance for the senior disabled site, and we're actually having a through street, and she really greatly reduced the amount of impervious surfaces.

756
01:09:28,227 --> 01:09:39,229
[SPEAKER_02]: So having a through street afforded us actually, you know, more open grave landscapes than if we would have to have separate entrances, like we have now, and except for the private apartments,

757
01:09:46,057 --> 01:09:46,517
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

758
01:09:46,537 --> 01:09:48,258
[SPEAKER_13]: Madam President, I may just make two comments.

759
01:09:48,918 --> 01:09:53,280
[SPEAKER_13]: One is that the arborist who has come out and studied the trees, you're absolutely correct.

760
01:09:53,600 --> 01:09:55,641
[SPEAKER_13]: The number of trees is irrelevant.

761
01:09:56,061 --> 01:10:01,943
[SPEAKER_13]: But what they've told us is that there are a number of trees there that are not healthy and that will be replaced by healthy trees.

762
01:10:02,943 --> 01:10:11,387
[SPEAKER_13]: Secondly, is insofar as the solar is concerned, the Housing Authority has been one of the leaders of that in the community.

763
01:10:11,527 --> 01:10:14,588
[SPEAKER_13]: We've had solar on 121 Riverside for the last 12 years.

764
01:10:15,608 --> 01:10:15,748
[SPEAKER_17]: great.

765
01:10:16,028 --> 01:10:16,448
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you for that.

766
01:10:16,488 --> 01:10:18,369
[SPEAKER_17]: And I didn't mean to be dismissive of the number of trees.

767
01:10:18,409 --> 01:10:19,909
[SPEAKER_17]: It's just not just not equal.

768
01:10:19,969 --> 01:10:22,530
[SPEAKER_17]: So of course, Tom, we'll go.

769
01:10:22,650 --> 01:10:23,970
[SPEAKER_17]: We'll see if any other residents want to speak.

770
01:10:23,990 --> 01:10:24,890
[SPEAKER_17]: We'll come back to you.

771
01:10:24,910 --> 01:10:26,831
[SPEAKER_17]: Does anyone else would like to speak?

772
01:10:28,371 --> 01:10:29,431
[SPEAKER_17]: Or sorry, Marianne's behind you.

773
01:10:34,592 --> 01:10:36,193
[SPEAKER_07]: Marianne, I do see two North Street.

774
01:10:37,053 --> 01:10:41,514
[SPEAKER_07]: I want to add a few comments here about the public meetings.

775
01:10:42,690 --> 01:10:44,832
[SPEAKER_07]: Gabe said there were about seven public meetings.

776
01:10:45,093 --> 01:10:47,815
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the very... Resident meetings, yeah.

777
01:10:48,236 --> 01:10:55,522
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the first one was for Director Butters, which was... I think the first one was only attended by a couple of people.

778
01:10:56,904 --> 01:11:08,014
[SPEAKER_07]: And after the January meeting, the next meeting was in April, and the January meeting, I don't know, there was probably about 15 or 20 outside residents there.

779
01:11:09,236 --> 01:11:20,523
[SPEAKER_07]: So when the April meeting came along, the housing authority doesn't know this, but I personally spent $200 of my own money and peppered the whole neighborhood with flyers about the meeting.

780
01:11:20,623 --> 01:11:26,486
[SPEAKER_07]: That's why you had so many people at your April meeting, because I notified a lot of people.

781
01:11:27,306 --> 01:11:36,932
[SPEAKER_07]: The other comment I heard is because the neighborhood meetings were held at 6.30, parents with kids were feeding their kids at that time, putting them to bed.

782
01:11:37,252 --> 01:11:38,513
[SPEAKER_07]: They couldn't come to meetings.

783
01:11:39,098 --> 01:11:40,179
[SPEAKER_07]: Other people were working.

784
01:11:40,699 --> 01:11:48,125
[SPEAKER_07]: So the other meetings, I would say, tops 20 people from the neighborhood, you think?

785
01:11:52,348 --> 01:11:58,552
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, some of the, you also have to consider that there were some- Yeah, Marion, if you could just direct me.

786
01:11:58,572 --> 01:12:04,097
[SPEAKER_07]: You also have to consider that some of those people who attended the evening meeting were Walkling Court residents.

787
01:12:04,737 --> 01:12:07,419
[SPEAKER_07]: So they weren't all residents from the neighborhood.

788
01:12:08,691 --> 01:12:09,932
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, so that's that point.

789
01:12:11,633 --> 01:12:22,500
[SPEAKER_07]: As you all know that I went around with a petition, almost 99% of the people I talked to beyond the immediate area knew nothing about this.

790
01:12:23,801 --> 01:12:27,683
[SPEAKER_07]: So there hasn't really been a lot of communication to the rest of the neighborhood.

791
01:12:30,245 --> 01:12:36,789
[SPEAKER_07]: As far as the traffic, the traffic that has been addressed tonight is primarily

792
01:12:37,863 --> 01:12:42,284
[SPEAKER_07]: inside the complex, but there are issues outside the complex.

793
01:12:42,544 --> 01:12:45,505
[SPEAKER_07]: For instance, the North Street Bridge is very steep.

794
01:12:46,165 --> 01:12:47,045
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the truck route.

795
01:12:47,525 --> 01:12:53,647
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the route that the trucks use to bring supplies to Whole Foods and the liquor store, because they can't go on Route 16.

796
01:12:54,627 --> 01:13:05,810
[SPEAKER_07]: When you have an 18-wheeler fully loaded with supplies coming over that North Street Bridge, gaining momentum on the way down, if someone should come out, either from Marshall Street or from the complex,

797
01:13:06,927 --> 01:13:10,408
[SPEAKER_07]: that truck may not be able to stop in time if they come out without looking.

798
01:13:11,948 --> 01:13:22,370
[SPEAKER_07]: So while they've addressed the concerns inside the complex, there are other concerns outside the complex that would be very difficult to address with traffic calming measures.

799
01:13:22,390 --> 01:13:32,171
[SPEAKER_07]: For instance, I don't think a speed bump at the end of the North Street Bridge would be good because cars have to accelerate to gain momentum to get up the hill.

800
01:13:33,312 --> 01:13:35,512
[SPEAKER_07]: And on the way down, that's not gonna work either.

801
01:13:36,840 --> 01:13:43,523
[SPEAKER_07]: Um, even though there are one way streets all around the complex now people violate that they go down the wrong way.

802
01:13:44,104 --> 01:13:48,846
[SPEAKER_07]: And that will happen even if you put one way signs everywhere, people will still violate that.

803
01:13:49,887 --> 01:13:55,469
[SPEAKER_07]: So as far as the traffic issues, that's still a concern to the neighborhood outside walking court.

804
01:13:56,570 --> 01:14:00,372
[SPEAKER_07]: Um, as far as, um,

805
01:14:02,206 --> 01:14:05,548
[SPEAKER_07]: There's been some talk about the Elizabeth Grady buildings and so forth.

806
01:14:06,428 --> 01:14:13,392
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know if the housing authority realizes that the Elizabeth Grady building has been given permission to demolish the building.

807
01:14:13,972 --> 01:14:19,656
[SPEAKER_07]: And they have changed the zoning for that whole property to allow for six story lab and office space there.

808
01:14:20,336 --> 01:14:25,199
[SPEAKER_07]: Elizabeth Grady also bought the property on the corner of North Street and Boston Ave.

809
01:14:25,559 --> 01:14:27,460
[SPEAKER_07]: So he owns the property from

810
01:14:28,062 --> 01:14:30,223
[SPEAKER_07]: the tracks all the way out to Boston Ave.

811
01:14:30,723 --> 01:14:33,724
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, about three months back, he applied.

812
01:14:35,225 --> 01:14:40,547
[SPEAKER_07]: He had a developer that was interested in buying that lot to put that six-story lab and office space building up there.

813
01:14:40,987 --> 01:14:42,408
[SPEAKER_07]: The deal happened to fall through.

814
01:14:42,888 --> 01:14:43,288
[SPEAKER_07]: However,

815
01:14:44,608 --> 01:14:48,049
[SPEAKER_07]: He's bought that property with the intention of selling the whole lot.

816
01:14:48,369 --> 01:14:49,829
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's going to come down the road.

817
01:14:50,429 --> 01:15:06,813
[SPEAKER_07]: When Elizabeth Grady builds that building and 200 Boston Ave, who also just got permission to build on top of their parking garage, a building equal in size to the building currently on the tracks, there'll be more workers that will be coming to those buildings.

818
01:15:06,833 --> 01:15:08,473
[SPEAKER_07]: So that will increase the traffic

819
01:15:09,915 --> 01:15:13,036
[SPEAKER_07]: North Street, and Boston Ave, all around the whole complex.

820
01:15:13,477 --> 01:15:26,563
[SPEAKER_07]: So there are gonna be traffic issues outside the complex that haven't been addressed here, or actually really can't be addressed at this point, because they've been concentrating on the traffic inside, which is reasonable, because you want it to be safe also.

821
01:15:28,704 --> 01:15:37,948
[SPEAKER_07]: As far as the buildings that are on the complex today that are near the railroad tracks, yes, there are three, but they're perpendicular to the track, not parallel to the track,

822
01:15:38,443 --> 01:15:40,204
[SPEAKER_07]: as the new complex is gonna be.

823
01:15:40,925 --> 01:15:48,971
[SPEAKER_07]: So the short end of the building, the stairway is against the railroad tracks so that the apartments are facing away from the tracks.

824
01:15:52,153 --> 01:16:01,800
[SPEAKER_07]: So the other issue is the housing authority had residents sign a couple of form letters that mentions there are benefits to the surrounding neighborhood.

825
01:16:02,320 --> 01:16:04,702
[SPEAKER_07]: So what are those benefits?

826
01:16:05,782 --> 01:16:12,648
[SPEAKER_07]: We in the neighborhood haven't heard how this complex is going to benefit the residential area around Walkling Court.

827
01:16:14,249 --> 01:16:19,834
[SPEAKER_07]: So maybe you have some ideas on that or you'd like to address that.

828
01:16:20,935 --> 01:16:23,237
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's what I'd like to hear about.

829
01:16:23,918 --> 01:16:24,198
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

830
01:16:25,139 --> 01:16:28,282
[SPEAKER_17]: If you'd like to address any of that, do you want to talk about the benefits to the surrounding area?

831
01:16:31,757 --> 01:16:38,160
[SPEAKER_13]: First, I'd like to say that I don't agree with what was stated in a number of instances, and I'm not here to debate that.

832
01:16:39,261 --> 01:16:49,146
[SPEAKER_13]: I will say that the benefit to the community is that we are providing a resource that is necessary.

833
01:16:49,886 --> 01:16:57,930
[SPEAKER_13]: We are providing a resource to the individuals who live in that immediate area when they no longer can afford to live in that immediate area.

834
01:16:59,080 --> 01:17:01,801
[SPEAKER_13]: and we are providing a resource to the community.

835
01:17:03,341 --> 01:17:09,583
[SPEAKER_13]: That's the greater good by providing additional affordable housing to folks who otherwise wouldn't have that.

836
01:17:10,003 --> 01:17:12,884
[SPEAKER_13]: As Gabe indicated earlier, we have thousands of people on our wait list.

837
01:17:13,804 --> 01:17:18,345
[SPEAKER_13]: We're looking to assist those folks who live in the city of Medford.

838
01:17:19,646 --> 01:17:21,866
[SPEAKER_13]: The immediate benefit to the community

839
01:17:24,714 --> 01:17:27,737
[SPEAKER_13]: meet the residents in that area off the property.

840
01:17:28,258 --> 01:17:31,861
[SPEAKER_13]: We've discussed that with the neighbors at the meetings.

841
01:17:32,282 --> 01:17:41,171
[SPEAKER_13]: We've discussed the ability for the neighbors to be able to still come on the property and traverse over the property to go to the grocery store next door.

842
01:17:41,641 --> 01:17:52,192
[SPEAKER_13]: We have indicated that we're attempting to be a good neighbor in so far as the way that we scaled the property so that the larger buildings are at the back of the property.

843
01:17:52,412 --> 01:17:57,277
[SPEAKER_13]: They are not parallel to the railroad, but they're designed so that it mitigates the noise.

844
01:17:58,017 --> 01:18:07,783
[SPEAKER_13]: The townhouses that are adjacent to the private homes have been done with consideration.

845
01:18:08,323 --> 01:18:20,210
[SPEAKER_13]: We'll no longer have the larger two-story buildings that are looking over the fence that we put up on our property for the residents who reside on North Street.

846
01:18:20,831 --> 01:18:26,094
[SPEAKER_13]: Insofar as the public safety issues, as far as the traffic is concerned,

847
01:18:26,505 --> 01:18:34,829
[SPEAKER_13]: We've met with the city, we've met with the fire department in particular, and it is they who have provided us guidance as far as the roadway is concerned.

848
01:18:35,149 --> 01:18:40,932
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'll emphasize something that Gabe said a few moments ago, and I think it was in response to a question that was raised.

849
01:18:41,602 --> 01:18:46,265
[SPEAKER_13]: We are going to have, the planning right now is that we are going to have raised walkways.

850
01:18:46,686 --> 01:19:00,855
[SPEAKER_13]: We are going to have attempts to mitigate the traffic going through there, whether it be with the design of the road, whether there's a bend in the road, whether or not there's parking, parallel parking, which tends to slow down vehicles.

851
01:19:01,576 --> 01:19:10,722
[SPEAKER_13]: All these things are going to improve not only Walkling Court, but also the neighborhood, because now we're not going to have people who are going to be driving all the way around up North Street

852
01:19:11,045 --> 01:19:15,649
[SPEAKER_13]: to come in the back entrance because they can easily access the property on Auburn Street.

853
01:19:16,090 --> 01:19:19,613
[SPEAKER_13]: So there's a number of things that we've taken into consideration.

854
01:19:19,894 --> 01:19:29,763
[SPEAKER_13]: The benefit to the local community as the executive director, what I've insisted on is to have community space there so we can reach out to the community.

855
01:19:31,164 --> 01:19:31,705
[SPEAKER_13]: It was mentioned

856
01:19:32,523 --> 01:19:36,566
[SPEAKER_13]: by either Gabe or Margaret earlier, as far as our resident services department.

857
01:19:36,907 --> 01:19:47,515
[SPEAKER_13]: My hope is to be able to provide services to the people in that immediate area from our resident services staff who are helping only now our residents.

858
01:19:47,816 --> 01:19:49,497
[SPEAKER_13]: But I'm hoping to be able to open that up.

859
01:19:49,817 --> 01:19:55,522
[SPEAKER_13]: We have a significantly large enough community room to be of assistance to the community.

860
01:19:55,952 --> 01:19:57,953
[SPEAKER_13]: for events if they want to have things.

861
01:19:57,973 --> 01:20:00,194
[SPEAKER_13]: We're going to continue to have that to be a polling place.

862
01:20:00,654 --> 01:20:03,135
[SPEAKER_13]: We're going to continue to provide services to our residents.

863
01:20:03,695 --> 01:20:09,458
[SPEAKER_13]: I've been at the Housing Authority since 2017, and we've increased our resident services staff significantly.

864
01:20:09,638 --> 01:20:15,060
[SPEAKER_13]: There's no reason why those folks can't be of assistance to the residents in that immediate area.

865
01:20:15,300 --> 01:20:15,900
[SPEAKER_13]: Today there is.

866
01:20:17,001 --> 01:20:23,423
[SPEAKER_13]: Today there is because the funding source that we receive is strictly state funding through what is now EOHLC.

867
01:20:23,443 --> 01:20:24,444
[SPEAKER_13]: It used to be DHCD.

868
01:20:25,140 --> 01:20:28,462
[SPEAKER_13]: And we're restricted from only assisting those folks who live on our property.

869
01:20:28,683 --> 01:20:29,603
[SPEAKER_13]: Going forward, we're not.

870
01:20:30,144 --> 01:20:33,706
[SPEAKER_13]: We're not, we have the ability, the housing authority has the ability to make that determination.

871
01:20:33,966 --> 01:20:35,568
[SPEAKER_13]: So will it be a benefit to the community?

872
01:20:35,888 --> 01:20:43,954
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes, it's nearsighted for us to be getting criticism that we're not going to be a good neighbor because we are.

873
01:20:44,434 --> 01:20:52,860
[SPEAKER_13]: And if I can just address one other thing that was brought up earlier, and that is that we are one of, if not the largest landlord in the city of Medford.

874
01:20:53,707 --> 01:20:58,673
[SPEAKER_13]: And we deal with elderly folks who live on family developments, and they integrate well.

875
01:20:58,773 --> 01:21:00,235
[SPEAKER_13]: They may have lived there for 30 years.

876
01:21:00,956 --> 01:21:01,716
[SPEAKER_13]: They haven't moved out.

877
01:21:03,178 --> 01:21:05,280
[SPEAKER_13]: They integrate well with the community.

878
01:21:05,661 --> 01:21:09,705
[SPEAKER_13]: And our housing manager for Walkling Court is here tonight.

879
01:21:09,786 --> 01:21:11,267
[SPEAKER_13]: She also manages family units.

880
01:21:11,748 --> 01:21:13,690
[SPEAKER_13]: Very, very familiar with the

881
01:21:15,518 --> 01:21:18,140
[SPEAKER_13]: administration of our federal units.

882
01:21:19,160 --> 01:21:26,624
[SPEAKER_13]: We're more than qualified to be able to do this and to ensure that the benefit is there for the residents.

883
01:21:26,925 --> 01:21:30,006
[SPEAKER_13]: And one last thing is that we're a public agency.

884
01:21:30,687 --> 01:21:34,609
[SPEAKER_13]: We are an open book, and that's why we're here tonight to provide you this.

885
01:21:35,370 --> 01:21:39,332
[SPEAKER_13]: And one of the reasons why I reached out to the council to do this

886
01:21:40,065 --> 01:21:49,809
[SPEAKER_13]: was I was contacted by someone who said to me, why is it that all the rich people are gonna live in the front of the development?

887
01:21:52,210 --> 01:21:56,991
[SPEAKER_13]: And they were told that because that was the word that was on the street.

888
01:21:57,632 --> 01:21:59,132
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think we've dispelled that today.

889
01:22:00,173 --> 01:22:00,953
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much.

890
01:22:01,355 --> 01:22:10,753
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you and I do just want to know something about as far as vetting process or public process as this is part of the plan development district or this has to be submitted as that.

891
01:22:11,455 --> 01:22:13,297
[SPEAKER_17]: That has been submitted to the CD board.

892
01:22:13,677 --> 01:22:15,339
[SPEAKER_17]: They will hold a public hearing, then work.

893
01:22:15,559 --> 01:22:19,763
[SPEAKER_17]: So public hearing again, they will work with the applicant to refine that.

894
01:22:19,963 --> 01:22:22,566
[SPEAKER_17]: That then comes back to the city council public hearing again.

895
01:22:22,666 --> 01:22:26,089
[SPEAKER_17]: And all along the way, there are chances for public input and any changes.

896
01:22:26,190 --> 01:22:28,392
[SPEAKER_17]: Are you raising your hand?

897
01:22:28,432 --> 01:22:32,115
[SPEAKER_15]: Even after we approve it, it goes back to public meetings for site plan review for details.

898
01:22:32,175 --> 01:22:32,736
[SPEAKER_15]: So yeah.

899
01:22:33,163 --> 01:22:42,049
[SPEAKER_17]: So it's, there's many, you know, outside of everything MHA is doing, there's a whole public hearing process as far as the zoning amendment that is needed to move forward with this.

900
01:22:42,069 --> 01:22:46,151
[SPEAKER_13]: Madam President, this today was just for informational purposes only for council.

901
01:22:46,231 --> 01:22:48,713
[SPEAKER_13]: And I don't mind taking questions or having to make comments.

902
01:22:48,793 --> 01:22:50,254
[SPEAKER_13]: So thank you very much.

903
01:22:50,274 --> 01:22:53,976
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, and I do thank you because yes, this meeting was absolutely at your impetus.

904
01:22:53,996 --> 01:22:56,318
[SPEAKER_17]: So I appreciate this and your availability to be here tonight.

905
01:22:57,839 --> 01:22:58,299
[SPEAKER_17]: Mr. Lincoln.

906
01:22:59,320 --> 01:23:02,562
[SPEAKER_17]: Unless, is there anyone else who'd like to speak for the first time who hasn't yet spoken?

907
01:23:03,883 --> 01:23:05,143
[SPEAKER_17]: Okay, back to you.

908
01:23:06,364 --> 01:23:08,804
[SPEAKER_16]: I realize this is a complicated process.

909
01:23:09,985 --> 01:23:11,865
[SPEAKER_16]: There's a set of societal goals.

910
01:23:11,885 --> 01:23:13,806
[SPEAKER_16]: There's a set of goals for the residents.

911
01:23:13,866 --> 01:23:21,368
[SPEAKER_16]: There's a set of goals for the housing problem in Medford, which is manifest and very, very large.

912
01:23:21,888 --> 01:23:29,330
[SPEAKER_16]: But I think it remains to be seen to some extent, and the devil is always in the details, exactly what the impact

913
01:23:30,127 --> 01:23:37,368
[SPEAKER_16]: or the proposed impact or the supposed impact or the predicted impact of the project will be.

914
01:23:37,848 --> 01:23:47,770
[SPEAKER_16]: I would suggest that most projects like this have some deleterious effect, perhaps in the short run, perhaps in the long run.

915
01:23:48,010 --> 01:23:53,751
[SPEAKER_16]: It's a question of balancing of interests.

916
01:23:54,351 --> 01:23:58,992
[SPEAKER_16]: I had one other thing that struck me and forgive me if I'm way behind the eight ball here.

917
01:23:59,788 --> 01:24:15,796
[SPEAKER_16]: On the noise business, if you put the building parallel to the railroad tracks, it strikes me that the noise will also reflect off the building itself into the neighborhood across the tracks, which it probably is not doing because the buildings are perpendicular.

918
01:24:16,177 --> 01:24:20,319
[SPEAKER_16]: Has that been considered in terms of the sound footprint or whatever you call it?

919
01:24:22,100 --> 01:24:24,041
[SPEAKER_17]: Can anyone from MHA speak to that?

920
01:24:24,961 --> 01:24:26,082
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm certainly not a sound engineer.

921
01:24:34,744 --> 01:24:51,012
[SPEAKER_02]: So, yeah, so the way the buildings are gonna plan to be designed, the mid-rise senior buildings, is that the acoustics from the train would kind of like bounce off, you know, would bounce off the building.

922
01:24:51,032 --> 01:24:58,296
[SPEAKER_02]: So they're not straight perpendicular, they're angled, so it would bounce off back towards like the train tracks, yeah.

923
01:24:59,017 --> 01:24:59,577
[SPEAKER_02]: That is the plan.

924
01:25:02,140 --> 01:25:06,901
[SPEAKER_02]: right, the building materials themselves would help absorb some of the sound.

925
01:25:06,921 --> 01:25:13,062
[SPEAKER_15]: And when we say neighborhood across the tracks, I mean the U-Haul building and yeah, the lab building.

926
01:25:19,763 --> 01:25:20,103
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

927
01:25:22,384 --> 01:25:25,604
[SPEAKER_17]: Any further discussion from councilors or members of the public who wish to speak?

928
01:25:25,844 --> 01:25:26,464
[SPEAKER_17]: Councilor Collins.

929
01:25:27,905 --> 01:25:29,725
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, President Morrell, and I appreciate

930
01:25:30,912 --> 01:25:40,898
[SPEAKER_08]: I know, like I said before, I know that there's been a lot of opportunities for residents, residents of Walkland Court already, residents of the neighborhood, residents across the city to hear about this project and to engage with it.

931
01:25:40,918 --> 01:25:44,901
[SPEAKER_08]: And I really appreciate that thorough and very long process.

932
01:25:44,941 --> 01:25:46,482
[SPEAKER_08]: And I appreciate the back and forth here tonight.

933
01:25:46,502 --> 01:25:59,190
[SPEAKER_08]: I think that's why we're all excited to have an additional meeting about this project here because often we do serve the role of public forum in addition to our more discreet roles as a city council.

934
01:26:00,750 --> 01:26:19,423
[SPEAKER_08]: And of course there, you know, there's a whole raft of specific concerns that I think we've been hearing from from certain constituents and it's really helpful to have this meeting where we can hear about how thoroughly they've been addressed and thought of and planned for and for myself as a representative, that's really comforting to hear, like Councilor Sang said earlier.

935
01:26:21,139 --> 01:26:24,541
[SPEAKER_08]: And especially having a discussion about, you know, what about pollution?

936
01:26:24,901 --> 01:26:25,521
[SPEAKER_08]: What about trees?

937
01:26:25,561 --> 01:26:26,162
[SPEAKER_08]: What about noise?

938
01:26:26,202 --> 01:26:32,124
[SPEAKER_08]: How indeed are we going to balance these various interests and make this the net positive for the community that we know it's going to be?

939
01:26:33,785 --> 01:26:41,008
[SPEAKER_08]: You know, for me, I reflect on what we started with at the beginning of the presentation, you know, the opportunity to create

940
01:26:41,653 --> 01:27:07,289
[SPEAKER_08]: really modern, state-of-the-art, more dense, increased in number, affordable housing, not just for any members of the community, because of course we have such a discrepancy between the amount of affordable housing that we need in Medford and the amount, even after this project, it's staggering, the number of residents who probably wouldn't even consider themselves housing cost burdened, who are, not to mention the people who are obviously in dire straits and in great need.

941
01:27:08,198 --> 01:27:16,705
[SPEAKER_08]: but especially to be creating state-of-the-art affordable housing for the disabled community and for fully accessible household units.

942
01:27:17,886 --> 01:27:23,790
[SPEAKER_08]: This strikes me as an opportunity for Medford to take a step towards being a leader in that regard, and that's a really special thing.

943
01:27:23,930 --> 01:27:24,571
[SPEAKER_08]: So thank you.

944
01:27:25,451 --> 01:27:26,252
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Councilor Collins.

945
01:27:26,272 --> 01:27:28,454
[SPEAKER_17]: Can I have my name?

946
01:27:28,474 --> 01:27:28,834
[SPEAKER_17]: Sure, please.

947
01:27:29,715 --> 01:27:30,736
[SPEAKER_05]: Name and address for the record, please.

948
01:27:31,416 --> 01:27:33,398
[SPEAKER_05]: My name's Barbara Vivian.

949
01:27:33,498 --> 01:27:36,440
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much for letting us all come in today, both sides.

950
01:27:37,028 --> 01:27:48,015
[SPEAKER_05]: I've been with the Medford Housing Authority for 15 years this month, and I've been the Hearing Officer and Reasonable Accommodation Coordinator for the past 12 years.

951
01:27:49,376 --> 01:27:59,843
[SPEAKER_05]: I hear many of the requests for a lot of the people in the state development that were on the second floor that could no longer do the stairs, and I had to move them down to a first floor if it was available.

952
01:28:01,264 --> 01:28:06,548
[SPEAKER_05]: And now I have people in our family developments that have children that are disabled,

953
01:28:07,053 --> 01:28:16,195
[SPEAKER_05]: that are in wheelchairs, paraplegic, many different ailments, and they have no way to bring their children up to the second floor to use the bathroom.

954
01:28:16,615 --> 01:28:18,255
[SPEAKER_05]: There's no bathroom on the first floor.

955
01:28:18,595 --> 01:28:28,417
[SPEAKER_05]: There's many people that have aged out in family housing that can no longer due to the stairs, due to COPD, due to neuropathy, and a lot of other medical issues.

956
01:28:28,977 --> 01:28:35,438
[SPEAKER_05]: And some of those families cannot move into an elderly site because they have families, they need too many bedrooms.

957
01:28:36,087 --> 01:28:48,336
[SPEAKER_05]: So the fact that they're putting a family site on this property means the world to me as a person who answers these and hears from people that are the least fortunate.

958
01:28:48,836 --> 01:28:59,104
[SPEAKER_05]: And right now I have to give them a Section 8 voucher and have them go out and search for a place to go that maybe they need to find a place with a ramp, which means that their housing subsidy then goes up.

959
01:29:00,245 --> 01:29:03,487
[SPEAKER_05]: And they need special accommodations for that.

960
01:29:04,035 --> 01:29:19,158
[SPEAKER_05]: So I just wanna say that from my position where I am, that this adding the family units there that have an elevator and have handicap units is gonna benefit our family residents as well as our elderly.

961
01:29:19,658 --> 01:29:20,579
[SPEAKER_05]: So thank you very much.

962
01:29:21,319 --> 01:29:21,659
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

963
01:29:27,240 --> 01:29:28,240
[SPEAKER_07]: Mary Anna Ducey again.

964
01:29:28,260 --> 01:29:32,181
[SPEAKER_07]: I wanna address something that Mr. Driscoll said

965
01:29:32,864 --> 01:29:34,146
[SPEAKER_07]: I went around with the petition.

966
01:29:34,586 --> 01:29:38,791
[SPEAKER_07]: I did not spread any information that was incorrect to anybody.

967
01:29:38,811 --> 01:29:45,478
[SPEAKER_07]: So if anyone got the idea that the family units were for the rich people, that was fabrication in their own mind.

968
01:29:46,419 --> 01:29:48,762
[SPEAKER_07]: I've lived in my house for 65 years.

969
01:29:48,982 --> 01:29:51,225
[SPEAKER_07]: I was there before Walkling Court was built.

970
01:29:52,798 --> 01:29:56,499
[SPEAKER_07]: My whole neighborhood has coexisted with Walkling Court for 60 years.

971
01:29:57,100 --> 01:29:58,660
[SPEAKER_07]: We're willing to do that in the future.

972
01:29:59,380 --> 01:30:02,462
[SPEAKER_07]: No one is opposed to putting public housing there.

973
01:30:03,342 --> 01:30:04,242
[SPEAKER_07]: We've lived with it before.

974
01:30:04,262 --> 01:30:05,383
[SPEAKER_07]: We're going to live with it again.

975
01:30:06,123 --> 01:30:16,867
[SPEAKER_07]: However, we need to have some compromise, because people think that the complex that's being built is too big for the neighborhood.

976
01:30:17,427 --> 01:30:18,248
[SPEAKER_07]: That's the first thing.

977
01:30:19,626 --> 01:30:23,388
[SPEAKER_07]: do not like the fact that the seniors are going to be along the railroad tracks.

978
01:30:23,988 --> 01:30:27,730
[SPEAKER_07]: To them, that's like putting them in the second-class position.

979
01:30:29,671 --> 01:30:41,416
[SPEAKER_07]: The other thing I heard from some residents is they called the housing authority, they told me, and they said that they wanted a public meeting here at City Hall so it could be telecast, so that people that couldn't come in person could see it.

980
01:30:42,077 --> 01:30:42,777
[SPEAKER_07]: It never happened.

981
01:30:43,037 --> 01:30:46,058
[SPEAKER_07]: They only had the meetings on-site at Walkling Court.

982
01:30:47,867 --> 01:31:03,834
[SPEAKER_07]: It may be a good idea, before you wrap up this whole project, to have maybe a public meeting here in City Hall, invite a broader perspective, maybe all the people who vote at Walkley Court, because they have a firsthand knowledge of Walkley Court, because they've been going there for years to vote.

983
01:31:05,135 --> 01:31:12,938
[SPEAKER_07]: So it might be a good idea to consider that going forward, rather than just having a small little community meeting with the abutters.

984
01:31:14,787 --> 01:31:18,069
[SPEAKER_07]: And you'll get maybe a broader section of concerns that people have.

985
01:31:20,530 --> 01:31:26,993
[SPEAKER_07]: As I told you when I presented the petition here, I got 1,131 signatures.

986
01:31:27,014 --> 01:31:31,756
[SPEAKER_07]: 99% of the people who signed were opposed to the plan as it's designed.

987
01:31:31,796 --> 01:31:36,519
[SPEAKER_07]: They're not opposed to having Loughlin Court there, but they're opposed to the design.

988
01:31:37,019 --> 01:31:42,442
[SPEAKER_07]: And I understand why they designed it this way, because they've tried to get as many people in there as they can.

989
01:31:43,616 --> 01:31:46,778
[SPEAKER_07]: But there has to be a middle road here.

990
01:31:46,798 --> 01:31:54,843
[SPEAKER_07]: And I know that that affects the funding because they have to have a certain number of people in order to get the funding.

991
01:31:56,024 --> 01:31:58,645
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a balance that has to be worked out here.

992
01:31:59,526 --> 01:32:02,708
[SPEAKER_07]: But the community is supportive of public housing.

993
01:32:03,288 --> 01:32:05,750
[SPEAKER_07]: We're supportive of affordable housing.

994
01:32:06,771 --> 01:32:10,673
[SPEAKER_07]: It's just that it needs to be reworked a little bit more.

995
01:32:11,934 --> 01:32:12,234
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

996
01:32:29,155 --> 01:32:31,776
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay, I've grown up in this neighborhood.

997
01:32:31,796 --> 01:32:35,177
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm sorry, just name and address for the record.

998
01:32:35,497 --> 01:32:38,458
[SPEAKER_14]: I've grown up in this neighborhood most of my life.

999
01:32:40,119 --> 01:32:42,180
[SPEAKER_14]: I literally live on the train tracks.

1000
01:32:44,881 --> 01:32:49,443
[SPEAKER_14]: Three years ago, you turned around and said to somebody,

1001
01:32:50,782 --> 01:32:52,263
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay, go and cut down trees.

1002
01:32:52,563 --> 01:32:54,564
[SPEAKER_14]: I had them there at 5.30 in the morning.

1003
01:32:54,804 --> 01:32:56,045
[SPEAKER_14]: I called the police department.

1004
01:32:56,065 --> 01:32:58,407
[SPEAKER_14]: The police department tells me, not my problem.

1005
01:32:59,827 --> 01:33:01,869
[SPEAKER_14]: Now, I understand about traffic.

1006
01:33:02,729 --> 01:33:04,750
[SPEAKER_14]: I've lived in this neighborhood for years.

1007
01:33:04,950 --> 01:33:06,211
[SPEAKER_14]: My street is a one way.

1008
01:33:06,852 --> 01:33:11,614
[SPEAKER_14]: I see people come up the wrong way, go down the wrong way, whatever.

1009
01:33:12,675 --> 01:33:13,415
[SPEAKER_14]: It's normal.

1010
01:33:14,376 --> 01:33:17,578
[SPEAKER_14]: But in this community that we're talking about,

1011
01:33:18,406 --> 01:33:24,588
[SPEAKER_14]: These people need help now, not next year, not today.

1012
01:33:24,828 --> 01:33:25,768
[SPEAKER_14]: They need it today.

1013
01:33:26,789 --> 01:33:30,350
[SPEAKER_14]: There are too many people out there that don't have homes.

1014
01:33:32,191 --> 01:33:35,052
[SPEAKER_14]: Like I said, I literally live on the railroad tracks.

1015
01:33:35,372 --> 01:33:40,073
[SPEAKER_14]: I'll tell you, in the last 10 years, I've had to replace 15 windows because of the trains.

1016
01:33:41,214 --> 01:33:45,415
[SPEAKER_14]: And now you want to put a third rail, and they're worried about a six-foot building.

1017
01:33:47,320 --> 01:33:55,322
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, I'm sorry, but if that six foot building turns around and eliminates a lot of that sound, then go for it.

1018
01:33:55,582 --> 01:34:10,586
[SPEAKER_14]: Because we have to house these people that are out on the street or have nowhere to go, they're disability, I'm disability, my house isn't just a lot handicapped and Rose knows that, she's been at my house.

1019
01:34:12,666 --> 01:34:14,947
[SPEAKER_14]: But I do what I have to do.

1020
01:34:15,993 --> 01:34:20,356
[SPEAKER_14]: As a homeowner, I have to clear off my lots like everybody else.

1021
01:34:21,457 --> 01:34:23,639
[SPEAKER_14]: These people can't clear off lots.

1022
01:34:23,919 --> 01:34:24,939
[SPEAKER_14]: They can't walk.

1023
01:34:25,780 --> 01:34:27,721
[SPEAKER_14]: I've met a lot of those people.

1024
01:34:28,202 --> 01:34:30,523
[SPEAKER_14]: I've known a lot of those people in Watling Court.

1025
01:34:30,684 --> 01:34:32,645
[SPEAKER_14]: Like I said, I've grown up in the neighborhood.

1026
01:34:33,325 --> 01:34:35,707
[SPEAKER_14]: I had to go through there to go to the Hobbs.

1027
01:34:36,167 --> 01:34:38,569
[SPEAKER_14]: I had to go through there to get to the high school.

1028
01:34:40,511 --> 01:34:43,773
[SPEAKER_14]: Sorry, it's necessary.

1029
01:34:45,912 --> 01:34:53,398
[SPEAKER_14]: And if you want to turn around and hear noise, come live at my house for two weeks and listen to the trains.

1030
01:34:54,399 --> 01:35:08,872
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay, traffic is atrocious no matter where you go, because everything is being dug up, rebuilt, or whatever, and they're sectioning it off into neighborhoods, not just ours, but everybody's.

1031
01:35:10,023 --> 01:35:21,451
[SPEAKER_14]: I came home from New Hampshire three days ago, and I had to detour so much around normal routes that I'm used to taking because of the construction.

1032
01:35:23,232 --> 01:35:33,600
[SPEAKER_14]: If they're willing to turn around and make a through street, because that's what the fire department is asking for, then by all means, make it a through street.

1033
01:35:34,140 --> 01:35:37,863
[SPEAKER_14]: But that doesn't mean that everybody else has to make it a through street too.

1034
01:35:38,893 --> 01:35:43,576
[SPEAKER_14]: And that, in my opinion, unfortunately, will probably happen.

1035
01:35:44,056 --> 01:35:52,682
[SPEAKER_14]: As much as I want this project to go by, it's going to create traffic regardless.

1036
01:35:53,262 --> 01:36:05,630
[SPEAKER_14]: We have trucks coming down West Street, which is a family run, that go into Whole Foods, go into the liquor store, go up into Boston Ave, because they can't go on 16th.

1037
01:36:07,108 --> 01:36:09,769
[SPEAKER_14]: It's not just North Street that hits the big trucks.

1038
01:36:10,489 --> 01:36:11,870
[SPEAKER_14]: It's West Street too.

1039
01:36:12,610 --> 01:36:16,792
[SPEAKER_14]: It's Auburn Street, Boston Ave, Winthrop Street.

1040
01:36:17,192 --> 01:36:19,693
[SPEAKER_14]: They're all in that community.

1041
01:36:20,394 --> 01:36:22,695
[SPEAKER_14]: They're all affected regardless.

1042
01:36:24,635 --> 01:36:30,498
[SPEAKER_14]: So yeah, you're gonna put in a lot more people in this housing development, but it's going to be a lot more

1043
01:36:31,455 --> 01:36:32,356
[SPEAKER_14]: friendlier too.

1044
01:36:33,156 --> 01:36:47,746
[SPEAKER_14]: And the one thing that I've gotten out of the meetings that I have been at in Auckland Court is they're also going to make community gardens, which is a big plus because they will be able to grow their own food if they want to.

1045
01:36:48,067 --> 01:36:50,568
[SPEAKER_14]: They will grow their own flowers if they want to.

1046
01:36:51,029 --> 01:36:54,651
[SPEAKER_14]: And that is only going to add more beauty to the project.

1047
01:36:55,932 --> 01:36:57,093
[SPEAKER_14]: These people right now,

1048
01:36:57,744 --> 01:37:01,145
[SPEAKER_14]: Like you've heard, a lot of people can't make the second floor.

1049
01:37:01,646 --> 01:37:04,927
[SPEAKER_14]: These buildings were built when I was coming up as a kid.

1050
01:37:05,007 --> 01:37:06,167
[SPEAKER_14]: My father retired.

1051
01:37:06,247 --> 01:37:08,228
[SPEAKER_14]: We bought the house in Medford.

1052
01:37:09,209 --> 01:37:11,589
[SPEAKER_14]: I grew up, went through school.

1053
01:37:11,870 --> 01:37:13,450
[SPEAKER_14]: My kids went through school here.

1054
01:37:14,911 --> 01:37:20,453
[SPEAKER_14]: And I don't turn around and have a lot of dysfunction, but

1055
01:37:20,829 --> 01:37:34,853
[SPEAKER_14]: This aggravates me of why people won't, I think a building going sideways would be a whole lot better than what we've got now because I listen to my windows rattle and roll every time a train goes by.

1056
01:37:34,953 --> 01:37:37,974
[SPEAKER_14]: So I can imagine what it sounds like in their apartments.

1057
01:37:39,614 --> 01:37:43,195
[SPEAKER_14]: And they weren't, my house was built in the 1800s.

1058
01:37:44,456 --> 01:37:48,477
[SPEAKER_14]: So I have a crumbling foundation

1059
01:37:50,000 --> 01:37:57,984
[SPEAKER_14]: broken windows, siding that's come off my house, gutters that haven't come off my house due to trains.

1060
01:37:58,644 --> 01:38:05,708
[SPEAKER_14]: To me, that's more of an issue to me, that people can get quiet time.

1061
01:38:06,988 --> 01:38:11,110
[SPEAKER_14]: Even for us, they have to turn around and figure out a way.

1062
01:38:12,171 --> 01:38:13,792
[SPEAKER_14]: In 93, they built walls.

1063
01:38:14,826 --> 01:38:15,927
[SPEAKER_14]: for noise construction.

1064
01:38:16,227 --> 01:38:21,551
[SPEAKER_14]: Why can't we have the MBTA build a wall for noise construction?

1065
01:38:24,553 --> 01:38:25,594
[SPEAKER_14]: Eliminate the problem.

1066
01:38:30,257 --> 01:38:31,038
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm just asking.

1067
01:38:32,019 --> 01:38:38,303
[SPEAKER_14]: But I think this is a great project to get and help families that have disabilities that can't walk.

1068
01:38:38,543 --> 01:38:40,545
[SPEAKER_14]: And as you can see, I don't walk well either.

1069
01:38:41,320 --> 01:38:46,622
[SPEAKER_14]: but I managed to get up the nine flight, nine stairs I have to get to, into my house.

1070
01:38:48,622 --> 01:38:53,103
[SPEAKER_14]: And I have neighbors, thank God, that help me during the winter to clear off my walkways.

1071
01:38:53,464 --> 01:38:59,765
[SPEAKER_14]: But again, I've been a lifetime member of Medford.

1072
01:39:00,245 --> 01:39:01,846
[SPEAKER_14]: I've worked for the senior center.

1073
01:39:02,046 --> 01:39:05,687
[SPEAKER_14]: I still volunteer at the senior center and I love it.

1074
01:39:06,607 --> 01:39:08,888
[SPEAKER_14]: And there's no other reward

1075
01:39:09,628 --> 01:39:12,350
[SPEAKER_14]: other than the seniors, because they teach you a lot.

1076
01:39:13,291 --> 01:39:15,192
[SPEAKER_14]: And you need to listen to them also.

1077
01:39:16,613 --> 01:39:24,158
[SPEAKER_14]: And unfortunately, a lot of them can't make it here because they have no way to get here to explain their views.

1078
01:39:24,238 --> 01:39:38,849
[SPEAKER_14]: Like they can explain it when we have the meetings at Watling Court, because it's a whole lot easier for them to get to Watling Court, where they live, and where they know what to do, than try to get here to City Hall.

1079
01:39:40,438 --> 01:39:45,540
[SPEAKER_14]: I happen to bring one of the residents with me tonight, because it's important.

1080
01:39:47,061 --> 01:39:49,702
[SPEAKER_14]: It's important that you have everybody's view.

1081
01:39:50,462 --> 01:40:08,770
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes, maybe the signs didn't go out like they should have, or they weren't notified like they should have, but this should be pertaining to, quote unquote, the neighborhood in progress, not somewhere down on

1082
01:40:10,064 --> 01:40:14,789
[SPEAKER_14]: on the Brooks School or down by Main Street.

1083
01:40:15,510 --> 01:40:21,697
[SPEAKER_14]: This is our community, and this is the people that you should be asking who, what, where, when, and why.

1084
01:40:23,479 --> 01:40:26,882
[SPEAKER_14]: And when we have the meetings at Rockland Court, yes, they do show up.

1085
01:40:26,982 --> 01:40:31,087
[SPEAKER_14]: The last three meetings I've been, there's been standing room only.

1086
01:40:35,607 --> 01:40:39,248
[SPEAKER_14]: And I agree with the developments because there has been standing room only.

1087
01:40:39,888 --> 01:40:43,509
[SPEAKER_14]: I get there early enough so I can make sure that I have a chair to sit in.

1088
01:40:44,809 --> 01:40:56,772
[SPEAKER_14]: But for other, there's no reason, yeah, granted they're 6.30 at night, but unless you have a toddler, I don't know any kid that's in bed by 6.30 at night.

1089
01:40:58,692 --> 01:41:00,793
[SPEAKER_14]: But again, that's my opinion.

1090
01:41:01,703 --> 01:41:04,786
[SPEAKER_14]: but I hope you take it into consideration, I really do.

1091
01:41:05,146 --> 01:41:07,228
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you, could we just get your name and address for the record?

1092
01:41:07,248 --> 01:41:11,291
[SPEAKER_14]: Sure, it's Rosemary Portrait, it's 78 Orchard Street in Medford.

1093
01:41:11,451 --> 01:41:12,412
[SPEAKER_17]: Great, thank you so much.

1094
01:41:12,672 --> 01:41:12,812
[SPEAKER_17]: Yep.

1095
01:41:14,494 --> 01:41:15,715
[SPEAKER_17]: Is there anyone else who would like to speak?

1096
01:41:15,735 --> 01:41:15,895
[SPEAKER_17]: Sure.

1097
01:41:22,901 --> 01:41:25,283
[SPEAKER_06]: Hi, good evening, my name is Jeanette Francis.

1098
01:41:26,324 --> 01:41:27,985
[SPEAKER_06]: And just address for the record too?

1099
01:41:28,962 --> 01:41:30,883
[SPEAKER_06]: My home address or street address?

1100
01:41:30,903 --> 01:41:35,164
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, you just give the street or you know, I'm the housing manager from Method Housing Authority.

1101
01:41:35,544 --> 01:41:37,464
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm actually the housing manager for Walkley Court.

1102
01:41:37,564 --> 01:41:38,845
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry, cut you off, go ahead.

1103
01:41:38,965 --> 01:41:40,485
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry.

1104
01:41:41,626 --> 01:41:50,508
[SPEAKER_06]: I just wanted to say that I know change is hard, but we're in 2023, we've come from 25, 30, even 10 years ago, things have changed.

1105
01:41:57,717 --> 01:42:05,483
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm talking personally and professionally, because I understand the importance of having affordable housing, because I've been there.

1106
01:42:07,305 --> 01:42:10,988
[SPEAKER_06]: Fortunately, I've been able to get a job here, and I've been here for 10 and a half years.

1107
01:42:11,668 --> 01:42:15,812
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'm very grateful, but I've been there, so I understand what it is.

1108
01:42:16,332 --> 01:42:24,959
[SPEAKER_06]: And as far as a housing manager's aspect, to be able to talk to someone that lives in the neighborhood, when they call in to find out what their options are,

1109
01:42:25,507 --> 01:42:33,875
[SPEAKER_06]: because there's not many options in Medford and not being able to give them one, that's disheartening to me.

1110
01:42:34,096 --> 01:42:35,397
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, to be able to tell them,

1111
01:42:35,956 --> 01:42:36,416
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know.

1112
01:42:37,036 --> 01:42:43,938
[SPEAKER_06]: Right now the waiting lists have X amount of people on it and it's basically not moving.

1113
01:42:44,879 --> 01:42:50,560
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not a great feeling to not be able to give someone options.

1114
01:42:51,240 --> 01:43:03,484
[SPEAKER_06]: And I just want to let everybody, the majority of the people that's on the waiting list is people that's in the Medford area that would like to stay in the town that they have grown up in and that they know.

1115
01:43:04,846 --> 01:43:07,448
[SPEAKER_06]: and not be forced to move out because they can't afford it.

1116
01:43:07,868 --> 01:43:13,511
[SPEAKER_06]: So being able to add more affordable housing to our portfolio is a positive thing for the community.

1117
01:43:13,571 --> 01:43:26,999
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, I understand change is difficult, but it's a positive change to move in a direction where the world should be moving to because affordable housing is a problem, not just in Medford, it's across the board.

1118
01:43:28,212 --> 01:43:28,952
[SPEAKER_06]: It's across the board.

1119
01:43:28,992 --> 01:43:34,516
[SPEAKER_06]: I live in Boston, and you can't even get past that waiting list because it's ridiculous.

1120
01:43:34,796 --> 01:43:38,378
[SPEAKER_06]: And affordable housing, as far as market rent, it's increasing.

1121
01:43:39,639 --> 01:43:40,359
[SPEAKER_06]: It's increasing.

1122
01:43:40,460 --> 01:43:50,586
[SPEAKER_06]: So a lot of people, and everything is not balancing out in our society as far as affordable jobs that be able to make you be able to afford what the rent cost is right now.

1123
01:43:50,666 --> 01:43:53,988
[SPEAKER_06]: So being able to have affordable housing in your neighborhood is a positive thing.

1124
01:43:55,046 --> 01:43:56,268
[SPEAKER_06]: And it's the balance.

1125
01:43:56,348 --> 01:44:11,387
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, we're not looking to take over the city of Medford, but we would just like to be able to provide housing for the people that's here that loves Medford and don't want to move out and would like to stay here and not be forced to move out because they can't afford it.

1126
01:44:12,548 --> 01:44:25,571
[SPEAKER_06]: So I just wanted to just say that piece and I just wish that I can't wait to see what the outcome is this I'm hoping we're able to move forward and I'm excited to be part of this new development.

1127
01:44:25,751 --> 01:44:26,151
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

1128
01:44:26,511 --> 01:44:26,871
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1129
01:44:29,712 --> 01:44:31,933
[SPEAKER_17]: Any other members of the public wish to speak.

1130
01:44:32,933 --> 01:44:33,273
[SPEAKER_17]: Come on up.

1131
01:44:44,783 --> 01:44:46,524
[SPEAKER_17]: And just name and address for the record, please.

1132
01:44:46,564 --> 01:44:46,965
[SPEAKER_01]: Sure.

1133
01:44:47,745 --> 01:44:54,370
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm Deborah Gage, and I proudly live at 14 Wackling Court in Medford.

1134
01:44:54,811 --> 01:45:00,795
[SPEAKER_01]: And I've been there for 12 years of my more than 20 years in Medford.

1135
01:45:02,977 --> 01:45:05,799
[SPEAKER_01]: I worked in academia for 23 years.

1136
01:45:07,100 --> 01:45:13,665
[SPEAKER_01]: And I was a volunteer English teacher in the community center at Wackling Court

1137
01:45:14,108 --> 01:45:20,152
[SPEAKER_01]: for five years until the pandemic, unfortunately, befell all of us.

1138
01:45:20,613 --> 01:45:32,081
[SPEAKER_01]: I just wanted you to hear from somebody who lives there because I've met retired nurses, bankers, gas station owners, bakery owners.

1139
01:45:33,690 --> 01:45:36,172
[SPEAKER_01]: teachers at Walkling Court.

1140
01:45:37,032 --> 01:45:47,477
[SPEAKER_01]: And I don't want anyone to think that Walkling Court is sort of the thing we have to tolerate instead of the neighborhood we could enjoy.

1141
01:45:48,398 --> 01:45:56,722
[SPEAKER_01]: So I just want you to know that I love living at Walkling Court, but I can hardly wait until we've got elevators.

1142
01:45:57,623 --> 01:45:58,003
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay?

1143
01:45:58,503 --> 01:45:59,664
[SPEAKER_01]: and I wish you all well.

1144
01:46:00,024 --> 01:46:07,508
[SPEAKER_01]: This was my first city council meeting, very interesting, but you all talk very fast, okay?

1145
01:46:11,030 --> 01:46:11,430
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1146
01:46:12,150 --> 01:46:16,813
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, I think we've all, I think we've all gotten that note a few times in our life.

1147
01:46:16,893 --> 01:46:17,313
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1148
01:46:24,657 --> 01:46:27,038
[SPEAKER_17]: Any other members of the public wish to speak?

1149
01:46:30,623 --> 01:46:32,224
[SPEAKER_17]: Any further discussion from the council?

1150
01:46:32,884 --> 01:46:33,664
[SPEAKER_17]: Or do I have a motion?

1151
01:46:37,145 --> 01:46:38,306
[SPEAKER_17]: Do I receive and place on file?

1152
01:46:38,746 --> 01:46:40,086
[SPEAKER_17]: Or is there a paper?

1153
01:46:42,227 --> 01:46:45,428
[SPEAKER_04]: Technically, the meeting is a paper.

1154
01:46:52,751 --> 01:46:58,893
[SPEAKER_17]: On the motion of Vice President Behrs to receive and place on file and adjourn, seconded by Councilor Sang, Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1155
01:47:06,240 --> 01:47:06,660
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

1156
01:47:07,320 --> 01:47:07,540
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

1157
01:47:07,580 --> 01:47:07,680
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

1158
01:47:07,700 --> 01:47:07,961
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

1159
01:47:09,181 --> 01:47:09,341
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

1160
01:47:09,361 --> 01:47:13,322
[SPEAKER_04]: Six in the affirmative, zero in the negative, one absent.

1161
01:47:13,342 --> 01:47:13,882
[SPEAKER_04]: Motion passes.

1162
01:47:14,282 --> 01:47:16,163
[SPEAKER_04]: Meeting is adjourned.

1163
01:47:16,323 --> 01:47:16,643
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you all.

